    [self.centuries addObject:prehistoriaCentury];
    
    NSString *prehistoriaSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString *page1 = @"<p class=\"first\">Her whole life had been marked by the events of that bright summer's evening. She and her father walked along the plains of Santillana del Mar, in Cantabria. The sun, almost setting, obliquely lit the path and the forest that surrounded it. And suddenly, she saw it. Intrepid and imaginative, as she had always been, she abruptly let go of her father's hand and squeezed through the narrow opening that the sunlight revealed between the leaves and branches that obscured it. After all, another girl more or less her age, called Alice, had discovered a wondrous world sliding down a hole. Frightened by her sudden disappearance, her father called her name, anxious and insistent, but powerless to do anything as he simply could not fit through such a narrow opening. She took her time in returning. At first with fear, then with curiosity, and finally with fascination, she became absorbed in looking upon the strange drawings that appeared, without rhyme or reason, along the length and width of the ceiling, weakly lit by the last rays of the sun before the dusk that was fast approaching. Finally, a hoarse and desperate call from her father: <i>Francisca, child, get out of there!</i> made her react. She emerged, over the moon, clapping and skipping: <i>How pretty, daddy, how pretty!</i></p><p>Well, the rest is history. It turns out that she had discovered the Sistine Chapel of Quaternary art. Of course she didn't understand a word of it, but she must have done something quite great because all those solemn and wise people were watching her out of the corner of their eyes with admiration and sympathy. There were also those that were envious and accused Francisca’s father and herself of forgery.<i>The cheek of it! Those paintings have been there fourteen or fifteen thousand years!</i></p><p>All these events occurred during 1879 and the exact place was the Altamira Cave, very close to Santillana. María Francisca Sanz de Sautuola was 8 when, in the summer of 1879, she discovered the drawings on the cave ceiling. The cave was already known to her father who, being an adult of decent height, had difficulty moving through its scant two metres of height. The girl's small stature facilitated her discovery and her triumphal announcement: <i>\"Daddy, they're painted bulls!\"</i></p><p>As an adult, she could systematize and digest the tidal wave of facts, theories, hypotheses and studies that were put forward throughout her youth. She learnt that prehistory is the advancement of the human species before writing. This long period of time is divided, subdivided, and divided again into periods more amenable to comprehension.</p>";
    
    NSString   *prehistoriaSubtitle2 = @"Cave Painting";
    NSString   *page2 = @"<p>During this dark and long 'night of time' our most primitive ancestors lived in caves to protect themselves from the cold, and their sustenance came from the hunt and wild fruits. Modern Homo Sapiens dispersed throughout Europe some 38,000 to 35,000 years ago, making way for a primitive art during the Magdalenian period known as cave painting, due to its being situated on the walls and ceilings of the caves they inhabited. Religious beliefs and rituals were already part of their culture; the figures represented were believed to have magical properties that would give favour either to their hunt, in the case of animals, or to social relationships, in the case of the human figures found not in the caves, but in the natural shelters in the warmer regions. </p><p>The artist would take advantage of the irregularities of the rock to give stronger definition to his motifs: an undulation might be the belly of an animal; a small natural hole might be used as an eye and in this way a three-dimensional effect was achieved. The paint was produced by mixing animal fat with minerals that provided the desired colours, basically blacks and reds, and was applied by various means: with the hands, with feathers or canes, with tufts of hair from plants or animals, sometimes mixing their colours somewhat like a pastel.</p><p>Horse, deer, bison, goats, and mammoth are the most widely represented animals, all of them in the Franco-Cantabric zone (the north of Spain and the south-west of France). </p><p> Due to the overcrowding of visitors and for conservationist reasons, the cave was closed to the general public and access restricted to investigators and scientists. The cave's entrance hall was, naturally, the first to be discovered. Its ceiling is 18 metres long and some 9 metres wide and while the cave was only two metres high, the cave floor was later excavated to facilitate visits. Because natural light does not reach other sections of the cave, the artist must have worked by means of some kind of artificial light source - perhaps tallow lamps? In the Madrid Archaeological Museum, Munich's Deutsche Museum, and the vicinity of the original cave, several replicas have been built.</p>";
    
    NSString   *prehistoriaSubtitle3 = @"Eastern Spanish Cave Painting";
    NSString   *page3 = @"<p>In Mesopotamia, the area that is present-day Iraq, between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, a revolution begun that rapidly spread throughout the West. Here, mankind creates agriculture and develops the granary, becomes sedentary, invents ceramics, discovers the wheel, polishes the stone, produces the first tapestries, and experiments with metallurgy. This revolution is known as the Neolithic period and took place around 5000 B.C.E</p><p>In eastern Spain cave paintings are different: they are from a later date (6000 to 2000 B.C.E.) and they are painted outdoors, in natural shelters or refuges. Their motifs are primitive pastoral and agricultural scenes, but gifted with an extraordinary dynamism and a great descriptive richness. In these men and women appear in a vast variety of activities: dancing, fighting, taming animals, digging a ditch, or gathering honey.</p>";
    
