    NSString   *edadMediaSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString   *page21 = @"<p class=\"first\">The long period of Spain's history known as the Middle Ages spans from the fall of the Western Roman Empire in the year 476 C.E. until the conquest of the Kingdom of Granada in 1492. Both in Europe and in Spain this long period of over 1000 years (or at least its first half) remains a forgotten, mysterious, and violent era and perhaps this is the reason for the passionate interest it tends to inspire today. Countless stories of superstition and witchcraft abound during these years.</p>Spain has been the field of a thousand battles and numerous people have occupied its lands. The Barbarians and the Visigoths came first, and later the Muslim Empire. Not all, however, was war and conflict. For long periods of time, Jews, Christians, and Muslims cohabited peacefully. All these ethnicities left a profound footprint in art and painting and in this chapter we will take a walk through several of them.</p><p>Rome occupied the peninsula, known at that time as Hispania, as well as a large part of Europe. The Roman people, learned and civilized, designated as barbarians all the peoples and nations that lived beyond the limes - the borders of the empire.</p><p>The nation of the Goths was the most numerous of the barbarian peoples: Visigoths, Ostrogoths, Vandals, Alans, Heruli, Rugii, etc. They lived beyond the Dnieper and the Danube. Pressure from other Asiatic peoples, the Huns, forced them into imperial territory, where they established a confederation with Rome: in exchange for land, they contributed to its defence. As such they fought in the Battle of the Catalaunian Plains (in the north of France) against Attila's Huns in the year 453. The Visigoths founded the Kingdom of Toulouse, but their defeat by the Frankish King Clovis I in 507 pushed them toward the Iberian Peninsula, where they already had some hold. Thus they settled in Hispania, establishing their capital in Toledo.</p>";
    
    NSString   *edadMediaSubtitle2 = @"Visigoth Barbarians";
    NSString    *page22 = @"<p>The Barbarians took with them the seed of their failure: civil war. The system of elective monarchy in the Visigoth kingdom fomented the ambitions of its nobles, the assassination of its kings, and treason. The following example is symptomatic: Wamba, one of the kingdom's greatest rulers was dethroned by a group of conspirators that, after a banquet, drugged him, and shaved off his beard and hair, which was considered very humiliating for a Visigoth. When he woke up, naked, he abdicated, donned a monk's habit and joined a monastery. In this case, at least, there was no bloodshed. The greatness of the Visigoths was centred on the reigns of Liuvigild and Reccared who, supported by the Councils of Toledo (assemblies presided upon by the archbishop), made way for a legislative body that was the backbone of the kingdom. In any case, civil wars among the nobility continued to weaken royal power until it fell into the hands of the Muslims in the Battle of Guadalete, in the south of Spain, around the year 711.</p><p>In the cultural sphere, which is after all what concerns us, the figure of Saint Isidore of Seville stands out, whose Etymologiae is a would-be encyclopaedic compendium of knowledge of its time and the seed of Hispania’s consciousness. In architecture, we can highlight the contribution of the horseshoe arch, the result of cutting the outer part of a circle below its diameter, as we can observe in the San Juan de Baños church in Palencia. Their craftsmanship in precious metals is very notable, including fibulae (safety pin-style brooches) and votive crowns (donations from the kings to the church at the time of their coronation). King Liuvigild managed to conquer almost the entirety of the Iberian Peninsula. His son Reccared, with his conversion to Catholicism in 589, maintained the foundations of the Visigoth kingdom until its annihilation by the Muslim invasions in 711.</p>";
    
    NSString   *edadMediaSubtitle3 = @"The Reconquista";
    NSString   *page23 = @"<p>In the face of the Muslim advance, Hispano-Roman and Visigoth refugees in the north organized in pockets of resistance that, sheltered by the mountains, began the recovery of lost territory (the 'Reconquista'), which lasted no less than eight hundred years. During this period a multitude of battles, both real and legendary, and an endless number of tales, true or not, of the miraculous appearance of saints and virgins nurtured a rich and dense history, wellspring of a literature and folklore that reveals a complex framework of political, social, cultural and economic relationships.</p><p>History and tradition merge to give rise to one of the most significant myths of the Reconquista. In 844 the troops of Ramiro I of León clashed with the powerful armies of Abd al-Rahman II. After several days of conflict, in the darkest moments of the battle, no less than the apostle Saint James appears on a white steed to tip the balance in the favour of the Christian band. The legend of this vision, obviously disseminated and embellished by the influence of the Church, extends throughout Christianity and is yet another element that solidifies the future Way of St. James.</p><p>The battle of Clavijo, in the vicinity of Logroño, brought to an end the onerous and humiliating 'tribute of the hundred virgins'. Remembering this era, Sorzano and Santo Domingo de la Calzada (close to Logroño) hold a procession of girls in wedding dress every year. According to this legend, the Christian kings were required to hand over to the Emir of Córdoba one hundred virgins in exchange for peace and tranquillity in conquered areas.</p>";
    
    NSString   *edadMediaSubtitle4 = @"Muslims, Jews, and Christians";
    NSString    *page24 = @"<p>Muslims and Christians and Jews cohabited peacefully (with the exception of some isolated periods) during the greater part of the Middle Ages. As the Christian kings made progress towards the south, the conquered territory was fortified with castles and walled cities.</p>";
    NSString    *page25 = @"<p>Ávila is a great example of one such medieval walled city. Alfonso VI of Castile ordered its construction at the end of the 11th century. According to tradition, not always a reliable source, construction lasted from 1090 to 1099, partly taking advantage of the layout of an old Roman military camp. In the following centuries continual reforms changed its original physiognomy. Not until 1982 was the wall freed from semi-detached houses. In 1985 it was declared a World Heritage Site along with the city. A good part of it can be accessed and visitors can walk along the top. Its dimensions are worthy of mention: it has a perimeter of 2,516 metres, 2,500 battlements, 88 turrets and 9 doors. The wall occupies 33 hectares and it is 3 metres thick and 12 metres high. Behind each of the nine doors there are one or several palaces of the noble families charged with its defence, each from between the 15th and 16th centuries. The Ávila Cathedral (1160-1180) is incorporated into the walled enclosure and its apse is yet another element of the fortification.</p><p>Islam in the Iberian Peninsula brought about one of the high points of European and Spanish culture. Unfortunately, for religious reasons its artists would not depict the human form; for this reason, their remarkable imagination and skill were channelled into literature, architecture, and decoration.</p><p>During the 10th and 11th centuries Córdoba, capital of the Muslim kingdom, was the most populated city in the West, rivalling Constantinople, Damascus, and Baghdad; some chroniclers estimate its population at a million inhabitants, a figure that may be slightly exaggerated. The Caliph's palace at Medina Azahara, today in ruins, and the great Córdoba Mosque, today still magnificent, are its most emblematic buildings. The latter began its construction in the days of Abd al-Rahman I (756-788) and housed some 5,500 people. Abd al-Rahman II expanded it in 833-848 and almost doubled its capacity. Al-Hakam increased that number to 15,000 and with Almanzor (978-990) 25,000 was reached. In total, more than 50,000 people fit into the Córdoban mosque.<p>";
    
