    // Section 3 - Romanico
    NSMutableArray *romanico = [[NSMutableArray alloc] init];
    NSMutableArray *romanicoTitles = [[NSMutableArray alloc] init];
    
    NSString   *romanicoTitle = @"romanesque";
    NSString   *romanicoCentury = @"XI - XII";
    
    [self.sectionTitles addObject:romanicoTitle];
    [self.centuries addObject:romanicoCentury];
    
    NSString   *romanicoSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString   *page31 = @"<p class=\"first\">With the year 1000 and its prophecies of calamity and apocalypse behind it, Europe in general and Spain in particular were covered in abbeys, monasteries and cathedrals whose chapels, roofs, and walls became depositories of Western culture. Medieval man is deeply religious and ever aspiring to knighthood and chivalry.</p><p>In this religious and chivalrous atmosphere two great artistic styles were developed: the Romanesque and the Gothic.</p><p>Romanesque painting emerges with a didactic and pedagogic purpose. Since reading and writing is exclusive to the upper classes, clergy, and nobility, the rest of society moves in absolute ignorance, taken in by strange beliefs, myths, and magical practices that, despite their limitations, acquire an admirable communicative and illustrative power. In this environment, painters as well as patrons try to establish ideological control over the masses. To this end, they do not try to imitate reality, but instead to idealize the message: paintings would have neither perspective nor chiaroscuro, though they would make use of a hierarchical perspective and as such more important figures would be depicted as larger to facilitate the viewer’s immediate comprehension, and figures are hieratic: without expression, often deformed, repeated, front-facing and with few details.</p><p>With regards to pictorial techniques, the bases of paintings in this period are the walls of monasteries, codices' miniatures and altar frontals. On the wall a coat of whitewash was applied, on which a coat of colours dissolved in water was painted. On this coat the silhouette of figures was traced, generally in black or ochre; these had their details filled in with various colours, normally very vivid. The completed work was then finished with tempera or another greasy material. Backgrounds were flat and monochrome, which would highlight the figures. The painting would mesh perfectly with the distinct architectural elements.</p><p>Romanesque painting in Spain had two main areas of dispersal: Cataluña and the valleys of the Pyrenees, and the kingdom of Castile. In the latter area, monasteries (Sahagún, Silos, San Isidoro, San Millán, etc.) and cathedrals (Oviedo, Compostela, etc.) are particularly outstanding. Monasteries and cathedrals are the driving force behind, and propagators of, artistic currents throughout the Way of St. James.</p>";
    
    NSString   *romanicoSubtitle2 = @"Monasteries, codices, and altars";
    NSString    *page32 = @"<p>The central fresco of St. Clement of Tahull, known as Christ in Majesty, is a good example that contains several of the most common elements of style of these years.</p><p>The technique used was fresco painting. On the wall a coat of whitewash was applied, on which a coat of colours dissolved in water was painted. On this coat the silhouette of figures was traced, generally in black or ochre; these had their details filled in with various colours, normally very vivid. The completed work was then finished with some greasy material in the same manner as varnish. Backgrounds were flat and monochrome, that is, of a single colour, which would highlight the figures. The paintings would mesh perfectly with the distinct architectural elements and spaces. The work of art put forward for comment (the 'Christ in Majesty') is a perfect founding manifesto of the Romanesque and fresco painting.</p><p>The central space of the main apse is delineated by a mandorla, a type of almond-shaped border, surrounding the figure of Christ Pantocrator sitting on a rainbow gesturing a blessing with his right hand; with his left he holds a book on which can be read: \"Ego sum lux mundi\". On either side of his head, each hanging from its own chain, the Greek letters alpha and omega appear, which symbolize Christ as the beginning and end of all things. He is surrounded by the tetramorph (the four apostles recognizable by their symbols: the bull, Luke; the eagle, John; the lion, Mark; and the angel, Matthew). The images of the Virgin and five apostles appear in the bottom frieze. This work is a manual of Romanesque mural painting as it contains all its characteristic elements: hieratic, front-facing figures watching the spectator intently and the vivid colouring of flat hues, without any depth of space and attempting to achieve volume through the creasing of the figures' robes. Additionally, the pedagogic nature and the hierarchic perspective are evident.</p><p>The image of Mary is another Romanesque icon that shows its presence in a vast number of churches. The vision of an apocalyptic Christ in this period starts giving way to the Virgin as the seat of Saviour and mediator between God and men. These are still hieratic and detached images, though they encourage the devotion and exaltation of medieval woman.</p>";
    
    NSString   *romanicoSubtitle3 = @"The Romanesque in San Isidoro and San Baudelio";
    NSString   *page33 = @"<p>The Collegiate Church of San Isidoro in León is a burial place with some 33 tombs belonging to León's nobility and royalty. Many of these were desecrated during the War of Independence, which took place between 1808 and 1814. During this conflict the French Army caused great damage to Spain's artistic patrimony. </p><p>The collegiate church, for example, was used as stables and the desecrated tombs as troughs. The collegiate church consists of a square space divided into six sections or naves by means of low columns, which gives it the look of a crypt though it is not one. Vaults and walls are occupied by delicate mural paintings from the second half of 12th century, very valuable and the best in Europe. In The Annunciation to the Shepherds, an angel tells shepherds, recognizable by the clothes of their time, of the coming of Christ. On a white background, characteristic of the mural paintings at San Isidoro, we see graceful figures of a firm and regular sketching. At the same time, it is a notable bestiary because of the number of domestic animals depicted.</p>";
    NSString   *page34 = @"<p>Situated on the border between the Christian and Muslim kingdoms, the Hermitage of San Baudelio was constructed at the end of the 11th century with clear Mozarabic influences. The Mozarabs were Christians who lived according to their faith in Muslim territory; hence it shows signs of Arabic and Eastern culture. This explains the mixture of tendencies the paintings showed, occupying all the architectural spaces of the building over a predominantly ochre base. The themes are varied, including numerous examples of profane motifs, such as the one shown, constituting a display of dynamism and movement. The paintings were sold in 1922 at derisory prices to American museums. Once sold, the new owners tore out the paintings and what can be seen today in situ are the holes that they left.</p>";
    
    [romanico addObject:page31];
    [romanico addObject:page32];
