    // Section 4 - Gotico
    NSMutableArray *gotico = [[NSMutableArray alloc] init];
    NSMutableArray *goticoTitles = [[NSMutableArray alloc] init];
    
    NSString   *goticoTitle = @"gothic";
    NSString   *goticoCentury = @"XII - XIV";
    
    [self.sectionTitles addObject:goticoTitle];
    [self.centuries addObject:goticoCentury];
    
    NSString   *goticoSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString   *page41 = @"<p class=\"first\">By the 15th century, the Way of St. James had already been influencing the historical and cultural path of the Castilian crown for many years. It is the way by which European cultural currents arrived, above all from France. In fact, the Way had been for European history the principal unifying element of the old continent. The discovery of the tomb of the first martyred apostle meant a point of reference and the convergence of different, already Christianized peoples. </p><p>Conscious of the importance of a relic like the remains of Saint James the Greater for its military and political interest -needing warriors and money in its fight against the Muslims that still inhabited the south of the peninsula- the Spanish monarchs contributed actively to the success of the holy path. The sovereigns of Aragon, Navarre, and Castile made an effort to attract to their dominions rich and powerful foreigners. The belief, more and more widespread, in the miracles of Saint James resulted in people beginning to undertake pilgrimages to Santiago de Compostela to receive his grace. After the first few pilgrims, distinguished and powerful, believers from all walks of life began to tread the Way.</p><p>The Way of St. James has always been entwined with culture, education, and information. All that was said, preached, told, sung, sculpted or painted on the path would all the while reach more and more people and places. Thanks to its influence in arts and literature, Santiago, together with Jerusalem and Rome became an important destination of Christian society. Today, far from having lost relevance, it is one of the paths most frequented by pilgrims and walkers in the world.</p>";
    
    NSString   *goticoSubtitle2 = @"Spanish Gothic";
    NSString    *page42 = @"<p>The Romanesque arrived by means of the Way and later the Gothic, a trend that was already predominant beyond the Pyrenees, followed it. The first Spanish Gothic presents a strong French influence in the first half of the 14th century, in the stained glass windows of the cathedral in León and in Alfonso X the Wise's forty miniatures titled Las Cantigas in the codex of the monastery at El Escorial.</p><p>Meanwhile in the Catalan lands, in Aviá, Catalan frontals painted using the ancient Roman technique of paint on panels using tempera still endure, using as binding agent egg and glue. The use of oil will become widespread during the 15th century.</p>";
    NSString    *page425 = @"<p>In other parts, Italian influences spearheaded by the cities of Siena and Florence arrive at the Crown of Aragon owing to Spanish possessions in the south of Italy. An artist in whose oeuvre these influences can be spotted is Ferrer Bassa. It consists of paintings forming large altarpieces divided into vertical panels, painted with tempera or oil, with golden backgrounds, without landscapes, with stylized and very expressive figures searching for spirituality. They represent the lives of saints or biblical stories; models are stylized, with elongated hands, thin fingers, pale faces and small mouths; their clothing shows rough creases (more characteristic of sculpture than of painting); reliefs (painted over models of jewellery or garlands) are prevalent, especially in Valencia. Checkerboard floors, which make an attempt at perspective, and the use of signs with inscriptions of the saint or the scene in Latin are also common.</p><p>Continuing the work of Ferrer Bassa is Ramón Destorrents, who is known above all for being the maker of the altarpiece for the Royal Palace of La Almudaina in Palma, Majorca, created in 1358 and now housed in different places, the main canvas Saint Anne Teaching the Virgin to Read in the National Museum of Ancient Art in Lisbon. Backgrounds are no longer flat nor monochrome, instead presenting a volume and colouring that highlight the principal figures, in which can be observed gestures, smiles, and a variety of emotions.</p>";
    
    
    NSString   *goticoSubtitle3 = @"Luís Borrassá and Bernart Martorell";
    NSString   *page43 = @"<p>At the start of the 15th century an international style spreads throughout Europe, as a result of the sum of French and Italian influences, in which Luís Borrassá and Bernart Martorell stand out.</p><p><b>Luís Borrassá</b> introduces the international Gothic in the ancient Crown of Aragon. He created a great workshop in Barcelona with numerous disciples and assistants, which sometimes confuses the authenticity and quality of his work. He achieves in this painting great expressivity and a dramatic effect: its colours, superimposed composition of the figures and use of space all stand out.</p>";
    NSString   *page435 = @"<p>Bernart Martorell continued the former’s work in the international Gothic style, although he already shows the beginnings of his shift towards the Hispano-Flemish variety of Gothic that is now spreading throughout Castile. He painted altarpieces, miniatures, and also designed stained-glass windows. Saint George Slaying the Dragon is a tempera on panel painting, whose brilliant colouring, the clean and elegant contours and the incorporation of the landscape as a key element of perspective stand out. </p><p>In tempera painting the solvent is water and the binding agent some sort of animal fat or other organic material. Historically tempera painting is characteristic of the European Middle Ages and of the Romanesque and Gothic styles in Western Europe and of Byzantine and Orthodox icons in Eastern Europe. The most common tempera painting uses egg. The egg-yolk is mixed with paint and water. The artist must be attentive to the proportions of the ingredients so that the mixture does not dry out or crack. Tempera painting dries quickly. It is applied in fine semi-opaque or transparent layers and facilitates great precision. Once dry, this produces a fine and matte finish. The colours of tempera painting do not change over time, whereas oil darkens, yellows and becomes transparent with age. It is applied on absorbent bases, containing less grease than the binding agent. \"Greasy over dry, never the other way around\". Most frequently used were wooden panels. Forgotten since Baroque times, today tempera painting has regained relevance.</p><p>The legend of Saint George is widespread throughout several European countries and is the patron saint of the Crown of Aragon. The original painting is today in the Art Institute of Chicago.</p>";
    NSString   *goticoSubtitle4 = @"The Flemish Style";
    NSString   *page44 = @"<p>In the middle of the 15th century, favoured by the powerful economic and political links between Castile and Flanders, the Flemish Style arrives in Spain, giving way to a vigorous Hispano-Flemish school. The use of oil becomes widespread, which gives more vivid colour and more varied tones, as is superimposition (glaze) and exaggerated detailing. All of these painters are considered to be pre-Renaissance.</p><p>Luis Dalmau, in the service of Alfonso V of Aragon, travelled to Flanders where he became acquainted with Flemish painting, which he introduced in Catalonia together with the oil technique. La Virgen dels Consellers (1343-1345) is an assignment by the Consell de Ciento (the council of Barcelona) for the city’s chapel. The use of oil allows a very meticulous painting technique displayed, in this case, in the architectural background behind the Virgin’s throne; also, an ample colouring and a greater capacity of depicting expressions. Much influenced by Jan van Eyck, Dalmau depicts a magnificent gallery of portraits of the consellers that assigned the work and can be found under the protection of Saint Eulalia and Saint Andrew.</p>";
    NSString   *page45 = @"<p>Jaime Huguet (1412-1492) heralds, from his maturity as a Hispano-Flemish painter, the new pre-Renaissance style. In his work one can see all the potential qualities of oil: bright colouring, some glaze, architectural details, checkerboard floors to impart perspective, and clear and expressive contours on golden backgrounds and stucco reliefs.</p><p> In the work Abdon and Sennen, Persian princes, are captured and killed in Rome. Above them is a Calvary and around them scenes of their life and martyrdom. In the interior frieze one can observe scenes from the martyrdom of the saints Cosmas and Damian, patron saints of doctors. The stuccoed frame is decorated with plant motifs.</p>";
    
    [gotico addObject:page41];
