    NSString   *renacimientoSubtitle1 = @"Introducción";
    NSString   *page51 = @"<p class=\"first\">The term ‘Renaissance’, ultimately from Italian rinascere, ‘to be reborn’, was used in that period not in reference to the art of its time, but to that of the Hellenistic period in Greece. All the thinkers of the era agreed that the spirit of Classical Greece had been lost in the tumultuous first medieval years. Nevertheless, that decadence had reached its end and humanists were gripped with a passion to save modes of expression such as language, literature, and arts, fascinating to a civilization such as the Italian that had grown and lived among ancient ruins. In Italy the Renaissance period is divided into the Quattrocento (15th century) and a golden, classicist age, the age of Leonardo da Vinci, Donato Bramante, Raphael, and Michelangelo, a period known as the Cinquecento (16th century). Patrons emerge who not only financially support artists, but also act as judges in matters related to art. Those who were considered craftsmen of painting, sculpture, etc. are now held as intellectuals who rub shoulders with the intellectual and philosophical universe of the time. These same artists, once taking shelter in the solitude of their profession, are now considered ‘scientists’ and dominate the arts and sciences. Once more the harmony, symmetry, and equilibrium of the human body are discovered and it stops being the exclusive domain of divine representations. Space, which is considered finite, continuous, and homogeneous is mastered, and perspective is fixed to the where the lines of the painting meet, the ‘vanishing point’. The theme of images, religious and biblical models still enduring, are progressively moving towards the profane, mythology, or simply to the human dominion “that is almost like divine nature” (in the words of Marsilio Ficino). If ideal beauty was sought after before, now a sort of naturalism strengthened by the capture and treatment of light is the goal.</p><p>With regards to the Spanish Renaissance, that has noticeable different to the Italian one, the predominance of religious themes is asserted, which is natural considering that Spain is in the midst of the Counter-Reformation.</p><p>The Protestant Reformation was a true religious revolution that in the 16th century caused the separation of several countries from the Catholic Church. The split was initiated when Martin Luther, excommunicated due to opposing the sale of indulgences, confronted the Catholic Church, supported by several German princes (1517-1555). The Reformation was a success in the majority of Germanic Europe and Scandinavia. The emperor Charles V was opposed to the movement and though he defeated the Protestants in the Battle of Mühlberg, the Peace of Augsburg in 1555 meant the recognition of the legal existence of Protestantism and the right to religious freedom for the empire’s subjects and states.</p><p>The Catholic Counter-Reformation was developed in the Council of Trent (1545-1563), defining and determining the Catholic reality in the face of the Lutheran Reformation, with an emphasis on Spanish theologists, especially the Jesuits.</p><p>Its late introduction explains its coexistence with Flemish models; during this century a powerful school of portrait artists emerges, culminating with Velázquez. Nevertheless, as in the Italian Renaissance, the technical treatment of light, colour, and composition are mastered already at the start of the 16th century.</p>";
    
    NSString   *renacimientoSubtitle2 = @"The Valencian and Castilian Schools";
    NSString    *page52 = @"<p>During the first years of the century, Fernando Yañez de la Almedina and Fernando de los Llanos work in Valencia.</p><p>Yañez (1440-1507) was one of the driving forces behind Spanish Renaissance painting. He worked in Valencia and Castilla la Mancha and is very influenced by the Italian Quattrocento and later by da Vinci, with whom it is believed he collaborated on The Battle of Anghiari. Some experts have attributed to him the copy of La Gioconda that is housed in the Museo del Prado. An important work of his career is his Saint Catherine of Alexandria; this saint is included in the group of holy helpers and is invoked against sudden death. In the painting appear the palm leaf, the sword, and the breaking wheel, all symbols of her martyrdom; the crown is an allusion to her nobility and the book a symbol of her wisdom. The influence of Italian ‘madonnas’ is visible in her face and her cloak is a recital of colours, creases, naturalism, and elegance.</p><p>Pedro Berruguete and Juan de Borgoña were working in Castile at the same time as the two aforementioned artists. De los Llanos is a close collaborator and associate of the former, to the point of their lives and oeuvre being confused; in an appraisal made in Valencia, both are called “pintors castellans” (Castilian painters).  There are authors that claim that he is the Fernando who collaborated with Leonardo. Juan de Borgoña (1494-1536) could count on the support of the Cardinal Cisneros, and under his charge he painted the panels of the doors of the altarpiece of the Valencia Cathedral that represent the Nativity of Mary, the Adoration of the Magi, the Rest on the Flight into Egypt, the Presentation of Jesus at the Temple, the Resurrection, and the Ascension. The landscapes and grotesques are Leonardesque, and additionally, in the face of the soldier kneeling on the left can be observed a copy of one of the heads painted by Leonardo da Vinci for The Battle of Anghieri. </p><p>Pedro Berruguete (1450-1503) takes part in the last stage of the Gothic period, introducing into Castilian territory the new Renaissance style and its characteristics: the mastery of space and the study of human anatomy, as well as variety and naturalness of gesture. Architectural and decorative elements are also present. In this work there is still a nod to earlier styles representing Saint Dominic in a hierarchic style. An ‘auto-da-fé’ was the torment that heretics condemned by the Inquisition received, in order for them to publicly recant their false beliefs.</p><p>Borgoña presents a more depurated painting technique than Berruguete’s and so the utilisation of architectural spaces, always open, the human figures, the use of light and colour, and all other Renaissance elements, make him one of the great painters of the era. The vast number of disciples and collaborators, in which his own son, Juan de Borgoña the Younger, appears, at times make difficult the exact cataloguing of his work.</p>";
    
    NSString   *renacimientoSubtitle3 = @"Sevillian School";
    NSString   *page53 = @"<p>Once the house of Aviz ended in 1580, Philip II annexed Portugal and its colonies to his dominion: “the Spain on which the sun never set”. Seville, gate of entry to the riches that the vast Spanish Empire generates and the financial and economic capital of the Kingdom, becomes a focal point for innumerable artists. In this city Pedro de Campaña, Pedro Machuca and the Extremaduran Luís Morales meet. The latter already heralds the characteristics of the following period (Mannerism) which we will comment on below.<p></p>Originally from Flanders, Pedro de Campaña settled in Seville from 1537 to 1557. Dynamism, movement, and contrasts of light are characteristic marks of his oeuvre. He worked together on numerous occasions with other painters, between whom grudges and envy occurred, which brought him back to his home country in 1563. He introduced Mannerism in Seville and also stands out for his imagination, his landscapes, and his architectural studies; with regards to colour, his palette increasingly approaches tenebrism.</p>";
    NSString   *page535 = @"<p>Luís Morales can already be considered a completely Mannerist painter who introduced this technique in Extremadura and Seville. Renowned for the pleasant religious themes he depicted, he was known as “the divine Morales”. One of his characteristic elements is an obvious lengthening of figures, whose contours he softens applying a Leonardo-influenced sfumato. The breastfeeding Virgin observed here is a recurring subject in this period. In Europe there is no objection against painting the naked breast, though this is not very frequent in Spanish painting. His backgrounds are dark, neutral, and the treatment of light inches us closer to tenebrism.</p>";
    
    NSString   *renacimientoSubtitle4 = @"The end of the 16th Century";
    NSString   *page54 = @"<p>The final part of the century is dominated by the portrait artists Alonso Sanchez Coello and Juan Pantoja de la Cruz. Moreover, a foreigner integrates into the Spanish artistic universe, who will become deeply hispanized, and will be the major representative of the fashion trends. We are referring to Mannerism and El Greco.<p></p>The portrait of Infanta Isabella Clara Eugenia is one of the most representative works by Coello, in which he exhibits an absolute fidelity to the physical traits of the person depicted and a scrupulous attention to detail, even insignificant ones of wardrobe and ornament. The Birth of the Virgin is a work by Pantoja de la Cruz. Though it appears to be a religiously themed painting, the impudent look directed towards the viewer of the central characters confirms the type of portrait that, in this case, lacks expressivity and psychological study, as is frequent in the Flemish style. The central personage, far from being a religious figure, is in reality Mary of Bavaria, mother-in-law of Philip III, helped by her two daughters.<p></p>The final phase of artistic development in the 16th century revolves, directly or indirectly, around the completion, with all its accomplishments, of the monastery of San Lorenzo de El Escorial. Spain experiences its imperial apex, under the long reign of Philip II (1555-1598), and a legion of artists of each and every specialty meet in Madrid seeking the approval of the monarch.</p>";
    
    
