    [self.centuries addObject:manierismoCentury];
    
    NSString *manierismoSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString *page61 = @"<p class=\"first\">Mannerism emerges as a reaction against the balance, moderation, and proportionality of Renaissance classicism. Michelangelo and Raphael took the first steps in this extremely personal style characterized by a skillful treatment of light, by the elongation and stylizing of figures, by the predominance of color over lines, by an exaggerated, foreshortened twist in the figures, and by the non-existence of empty spaces in paintings (the so-called \"Horror vacui\"). It is a refined and very affected style, fond of fantasy and paradox, falling, at times, into affectation, \"mannerisms\" (the origin of the term) and extravagance.</p><p>Broadly speaking, the Mannerist period chronologically coincided with the reigns of Charles I (1517-1556), Philip II (1556-1598) and Philip III (1598-1621), that is, with Spanish hegemony of the world. Military, political, and colonial successes demanded from the Spanish people a high spiritual tension and great economic sacrifices. The apex of said hegemony was in 1580 with the annexation of Portugal and its overseas empire. While the strong claims on America and the shipments of gold and silver that came from it lasted, everything went well. Nevertheless, with Philip II's bankruptcy at the end of the 16th century and the expulsion of the 'moriscos', ordered by Philip III at the start of the 17th century, a long and protracted decadence begins, turning Spain into a second-rate power starting in 1648 (Peace of Westphalia), 1659 (Treaty of the Pyrenees), 1688 (independence of Portugal) and, definitively, in 1713 (Peace of Utrecht). However, and in contrast to the above, the 17th century and the first half of the 18th offer the cultural and artistic splendour of the 'Golden Century', Spain's golden age.</p><p>With the diaspora of Italian artists caused by the Sack of Rome in 1527 the style was spread throughout Europe. In Spain, Mannerism was reflected in the work of Pedro Machuca, Luís Morales, and especially, El Greco.</p>";
    
    NSString *manierismoSubtitle2 = @"El Greco";
    NSString *page62 = @"<p>Doménikos Theotokópoulos (1541-1614), though born in Crete, developed his singular style and the greater part of his artistic trajectory in Spain. On his native island he trained as a painter of icons, before moving to Venice, where he got to know the work of Titian and Tintoretto, artists who, along with Michelangelo, were the most influential on his painting. In 1570 he is already in Toledo painting a great altarpiece for the monastery of Saint Dominic of Silos (the Old). Philip II commissioned a painting for El Escorial, but The Martyrdom of Saint Maurice did not please the monarch, who never dealt with the artist again. This entailed a great disappointment for El Greco as he aspired to be named court painter, but being already a sought after painter, in demand by aristocrats and clerics, he dedicated himself to cultivating his distinctive style.</p>";
    NSString *page621 = @"<p>His elongated figures, painted using fluid brushstrokes, appear to be immaterial beings, lacking solidity and imbued with an intense spirituality. This is combined with his extremely original palette of cold colours, achieving surprising effects with reds, blues, and whites, of a rare intensity and sharpness. The identity of the sitter isn't known with certainty, but El Caballero de la Mano en el Pecho (The Nobleman with his Hand on his Chest), one of his finest works, has passed into history as the Spanish prototype of gentlemanliness and nobility. Eyes with a deep stare in an emaciated face; virtuosity of the collar, cuff, and hilt of his sword, as well as an idiosyncrasy of El Greco shown in the pose of the hand and the separation of the index and ring fingers.</p>";
    NSString *page622 = @"<p>Gonzalo Ruiz de Toledo, count and lord of Orgaz (Toledo), died in 1323 and at his burial occurred the miracle of the appearance of Saint Augustine and Saint Stephen who, with their own hands, inter him. In his will the count left a legacy in perpetuity to the Church of Santo Tomé (Toledo). With the passing of the years, the locals forgot that obligation, and nearly 150 years later in 1586 Andrés Nuñez de Madrid, at the time the parish priest of the church, wins the lawsuit brought against the peasants, in this way recovering the bequest of the count. Part of the recovered income was set aside for the commission that the Cretan received to recount with his paintbrush the miracle that occurred, which sums up very well the Mannerist style that El Greco perfected: luminosity centred on the principal figures, the stylisation of the same, figures at times proportional, at times twisted, the predominance of colour, dynamism and movement of the scene, abhorrence of empty space, etc.<p></p>The painting has two levels. The upper is dedicated to divinity, glory, or Heaven, dominated by the central figure of Jesus Christ accompanied by a celestial court made up of the Virgin, Saint John the Baptist, Saint Paul, Saint James the Greater, Saint Peter, and others. The lower level is terrestrial and mundane; here the burial with the intervention of Saint Augustine and Saint Stephen is recounted. The portrayed personages are all real people from the 16th century, assisting, anachronistically, a 14th century burial. The parish priest, winner of the lawsuit, appears reading the rites; faced forward watching us is the selfsame author of the canvas, and additionally his son, lighting the scene with a torch and pointing towards the corpse. Between the two levels, an angel carries the soul of the deceased in its arms. The painting wholeheartedly agrees with the idea that there is a life beyond the strictly terrestrial one.</p>";
    
    NSString *manierismoSubtitle3 = @"The Altarpiece of the Monastery of Saint Dominic of Silos";
    NSString *page63 = @"<p>Created between 1577 and 1579, it is the first work that El Greco completes in Spain. Diego de Castilla, dean of the Cathedral of Toledo, and the testamentary executor of the patron of the monastery, María de Silva, commissioned it. It consists of 9 canvases divided into three sections, the central being twice as wide as those on the side. Only 3 originals survive (Saint John the Evangelist, Saint John the Baptist, and the Resurrection), the rest were sold and substituted by copies. The principal paintings are The Trinity and The Assumption of the Virgin Mary.</p><p>In the Trinity painting (clearly influenced by Michelangelo), the serenity and the anatomical study of Christ, the sadness of the Father that holds him, the helplessness of the chorus of angels, and above all the dove that represents the Holy Ghost stand out. The Assumption is a canvas in two levels, one celestial and one terrestrial. In the latter, two groups of apostles are separated by the sepulchre of the Virgin. This composition on two levels will later be perfected in the pinnacle of El Greco’s work that we have just seen.</p><p>In the historiography of El Greco, legal action is frequent, for the price of his paintings as well as for their composition or deadlines. In this case, a committee of appraisers set a price of 350 ducats. Furthermore, the canons of the cathedral did not accept that the crowd that hound Christ should be above the level of His head, and they did not agree with the undocumented presence of the Three Marys (the Virgin, Mary Magdalene, and Mary Cleophas) in the moment that the canvas recounts. Fortunately, the painting stayed the way the artist conceived it. The soldiers compete for the clothes of Christ and a carpenter, before the attentive gaze of the three Blessed Women, perforates the wood of the cross. The serene and illuminated face of Christ, his red tunic, the silvery greys of the armour and the ochres of the lower figures catch the attention of the viewer.</p>";
    
