    // Section 7 - Barroco
    NSMutableArray *barroco = [[NSMutableArray alloc] init];
    NSMutableArray *barrocoTitles = [[NSMutableArray alloc] init];
    
    [self.sectionTitles addObject:@"baroque"];
    [self.centuries addObject:@"XVII-XVIII"];
    
    NSString   *barrocoSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString   *page71 = @"<p class=\"first\">Towards the end of the 17th century the deterioration and decadence of Imperial Spain becomes evident. This included defeats such as in the battle of the Downs or of Rocroi (1642), diplomatic disaster in Westphalia (1648) or in the Peace of the Pyrenees (1659), attacks on its American colonies, and even harassment from corsairs, buccaneers, and pirates. All of this presaged a calamitous end of a century. In the heart of the kingdom, economic and social decay is manifest.</p><p>In 1609 occurred the expulsion of the remaining 500,000 Moriscos or Muslims resident of the peninsula. This population of peasants, artisans, and technicians left in a state of neglect the cultivation of rice, cotton, and sugar cane, and the leather, glass, and jewellery making industries, striking a mortal blow to the national economy.</p><p>In this declining setting, the Spanish spirit lived its most splendid cultural period, and its population withdrew into itself, exalting the immortal values of the earth and recovering equilibrium in human virtue. The characters of the picaresque novels by Cervantes, the theatre of Tirso de Molina, Lope de Vega, and Calderón de la Barca, the poetry of Quevedo and Góngora, and the paintings by Velázquez and Murillo and so many others expound the noblest desires of the peoples that continued to dream of an idealized Spain that did not know sundown.</p><p>Its name is derived from that of an imperfect pearl. The Baroque is a reaction against the pagan clasicism of the Reinassance. Baroque painting is characterized by the realism, rich and intense colors, strong contrasts betweeen light and dark (tenebrism) that tend to add dramatism to scenes that are passionate and twisted in impossible scorzos. The trompe-l'oeil treatment is frequently used, which consists on the creation of perception illusions by means of playing with perspective and other optical artifacts. New genres are born, such as still lifes, landscapes, portraits, and costumbrism. In Spain, in the middle of the Counter-Reformation, religious themes are preferred. </p><p>The Baroque is the painting of the Spanish Golden Age, and we could name three schools: andalusian, valencian, and madrilian.</p>";
    
    NSString   *barrocoSubtitle2 = @"Murillo";
    NSString   *page72 = @"<p>The work <i>The Holy Family with a Little Bird</i> represents a domestic scene treated with delicate gentleness and set in a family atmosphere, in this way achieving a mixture between the sacred and the profane. Two opposite figures, mother and father, with another central figure overly lit up to attract the attention of the viewer. The figures have their contours slightly blurred so as to diminish the contrasts. It shows clear influences from the contemporary Zurbarán and Ribera.</p><p>The <i>Adoration of the Shepherds</i> shows clear, though toned down, characteristics of Baroque, especially in the chiaroscuros, not as violent as in the case of Caravaggio or Ribera. The figure of Saint Joseph, quite blurred, divides the painting into two halves: to the right, the group of shepherds; to the left, the Virgin displaying the Child and the animals, especially the mule, in semi-darkness; the whole painting with an only guessable architectural background. Light originates from the upper right corner and traces a diagonal path, lighting the adorers and baby Jesus, whose reflection also lights the face of his mother. We can also observe two superimposed levels: in the foreground we see the old shepherd - whose bare soles are dirty and full of wrinkles, in the style of Caravaggio - and the mother with her child; in the background we see the remaining characters.</p>";
    
    NSString   *page721 = @"<p>In <i>Children Eating Fruit</i> Murillo shows himself as a great and famous painter of children, of their innocence and naivety, of their joy and their dignity in the face of poverty. Murillo escapes from clerical edicts, always with recurring subjects and works on around fifteen paintings that made up a masterful gallery that would become an artistic school in Europe. In all his paintings of children, anywhere in the scene, there is an unsurpassable still life.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The <i>Immaculate of Soult</i> is one of the numerous religious paintings made by Murillo. The models of beauty he used for all his paintings with this theme did nothing but increase his popularity. And, in fact, millions of reproductions of the work in prints, engravings or calendars are abundant even today. </p><p>In this case, the exaggerated luminosity surrounding the figure of Mary stresses the intention of magnifying the divine greatness of the Virgin. This work is so named in memorial of the French marshal who, following the War of Independence (1808-1814), brought it with him to France; its return to the Spanish patrimony took many years and a lot of effort.</p>";
    
    NSString *barrocoSubtitle3 = @"Zurbarán";
    NSString *page731 = @"<p>Religious themes dominate andalusian painting in the Baroque period. In general, the ideal of a serene beauty, the joy of spirituality, and the popular themes of a pure religiosity are sought after. In the andalusian School, grace prevails over intensity, tenderness over force, and benevolence over drama and the message of reconciliation.</p><p>Zurbarán is one of the best artists of the Spanish Baroque. He specialized in painting monks and convents. He painted monks in a wide variety of poses and situations: praying, eating, in mystical poses, and as protagonists of miracles or divine visions. He worked incessantly for monastic orders, enclosed or not, as the Carthusian, Hieronymite, Dominican, and the Mercedarian orders were. His style remained invariable, this immobility being the secret of his success, though it ended up condemning his artistic career. He learned to obtain from the monks' habits an enormous range of whites, as well as a study of their folds that approaches cubism; his clumsiness with composition and perspective is apparent, but he compensates it with a prodigious capacity for recreating materials, cloth, knick-knacks, hair, and smoothness of the skin. He covered a range of brilliant and joyous colours, such as purples, violets, emerald or dark greens, and lemon yellows. The best collection of his painting is conserved in the monastery of Guadalupe (in Cáceres), as it has been conserved intact in situ, following the original 17th century placement.</p>";
    NSString *page732 = @"<p><i>Saint Hugh in the Carthusian Refectory</i> is a good example of Zurbarán's mastery of achieving an ample palette of whites when painting the habits of his monks. At the same time, the L-shaped composition of the scene, with the position of the page and bishop, break the apparent monotony and stiffness of the characters. Saint Bruno, founder of the Carthusians, and his seven first monks were fed thanks to the generosity of Saint Hugh, the bishop of Grenoble. One day, the latter asked for some meat. The monks fervently discussed this request until they fell deeply asleep. They remained in that way for 45 days. When they awoke, considering the sleep as a divine message, they decided that there could be no exceptions to the rule that forbade meat during Lent, which was currently underway.</p><p>The legend tells that Saint Casilda, daughter of the Muslim king of Toledo, carried bread in her clothes to relieve the hunger of Christian prisoners. On one occasion, soldiers interrogated her on what she was carrying beneath her skirt; when she showed them, the bread had miraculously turned into a bouquet of flowers. Specifically, it is the luminosity of the cloth, the majesty of the dress, and the virtuosity of the brocade that are the most impressive parts of this work.</p>";
    
    NSString   *barrocoSubtitle4 = @"Velázquez";
    NSString   *page741 = @"<p>Meanwhile, in Madrid, Diego Velázquez de Silva (1599-1660) was working, one of the greatest painting geniuses in the world.</p><p>He is the best Baroque painter in Spain and a peak in the art of the world. At 10 he enters into apprenticeship in the workshop of Francisco Pacheco, whose daughter he will later marry. His first, Sevillian, period is Tenebrist, painting still lifes of a great quality and realism. He moves to Madrid in 1623 where he will be named court painter of Philip IV, whose family he will depict on horseback, hunting, or in ceremonies. He also paints portraits of aristocrats and of court jesters; all of them are gifted with a great realism and psychological depth. He paints mythological paintings, which were a novelty in the Spanish panorama. His masterpiece is Las Meninas, a group portrait of the family of Philip IV. What stands out in all of his paintings are his mastery of aerial perspective (his atmospheres seem to have dust floating between figures), the light, the linework, and the brilliant colouring applied with a loose, almost impressionist brushstroke.</p>";
    NSString   *page742 = @"<p><i>Old Woman Frying Eggs</i> is a work from the artist's Sevillian period. It is a still life with figures and a multitude of objects and kitchen utensils such as a casserole, a portable cooker, a wooden spoon, a flask of wine, a pannier, and a copper cauldron. The old woman could be the mother-in-law of the painter, and the boy an errand boy who also posed as a model. Here, Velázquez uses the technique of 'half-length figures', who appear very real and close to the viewer. The scene lacks movement; there is a great calm, as if the subjects had been caught by surprise in the moment. The dominant pictorial technique is Tenebrism, with contrasts of light and shade on a dark background. The old woman, who appears to be blind, feels her way with the wooden spoon. There are critics who suggest that this could be a reflection on touch, taste, and sight.</p><p>The painting <i>The Triumph of Bacchus</i> is also known as Los Borrachos (The Drunks). It is a mundane adaptation of classical mythology. Velázquez surrounds the young Bacchus with vulgar peasants. The influences from the school of Titian and Rubens in the treatment of the background and human body, respectively, are notable. The contrast of the nudes in the same composition stands out: one, chubby and pale, the other, tanned and muscular.</p>";
    
    
    NSString   *barrocoSubtitle5 = @"Velázquez, Madrid Period";
    NSString   *page751 = @"<p>During his stay in Madrid, Velázquez admired and picked up the techniques of Titian and Rubens, and later, in Italy, the works of Raphael and Michelangelo. The Forge of Vulcan shows the first step of his pictorial maturity, influenced by these great masters; his painting starts to become deeper, richer, and luminous, and his nudes more polished. Nevertheless, he still paints mythological scenes reflected in everyday life, with joyful characteristics and with a simple representation of human activity.<br></p><p><i>The Surrender of Breda </i> is also known as Las lanzas (The lances). All the characters in this painting are portraits of the protagonists of the historical fact; it is a photographic instant of the 17th century commissioned by Philip IV ten years after it took place. Two groups, victors to the right and the vanquished to the left, between two horses, play the leading role in the handing over of the keys to the city of Breda in the central space of the painting. The background is a magnificent battle landscape of clear shades that make the presence of the protagonists stand out. It is interesting how the painter decides to make the gentlemanliness and benevolence of the victorious Spanish troops stand out, whose general, Ambrosio D'Spínola, stops the vanquished from kneeling down.</p><p><i>Venus at her Mirror</i> shows the goddess Venus in an erotic pose stretched out on a bed and looking into a mirror held by Cupid. Velázquez discards any mythological connotation and paints a magnificent woman gifted with a body in white and rose shades. For the time, it was a type of work that was carefully monitored and whose dissemination was considered problematic; it is probable that it was painted in Italy, on the artist’s second trip. The most original element is the mirror, through which the woman gazes outward, toward the viewer who contemplates her. In 1914 a British suffragette made seven cuts in it with a knife, though it was soon fully restored.</p>";
    
    NSString   *barrocoSubtitle6 = @"Velázquez' Las Meninas";
    NSString   *page761 = @"<p>The original title of the work was <i>La Familia</i> (The Family), but in 1843 José Madrazo renamed it Las Meninas, the name by which it is now universally known. The painting contains eleven people and a pet mastiff, presided over by the Infanta Margaret of Austria. We see in the foreground a strong light that emerges from the first window on the right and takes us to the figure of the Infanta, the geometric centre of the painting, who appears to levitate as her feet are hidden by her farthingale. </p><p>Dark shades are predominant, though they are made lively by the silvery tones of the dresses and by the reddish touches around the scene: the cross of Saint James, Velázquez' palette, the vase offered to the infanta, her and Isabel de Velasco's handkerchiefs, and finally, the red stain on little Nicolas' clothes. </p><p>The atmosphere and aerial perspective created by the painter are repeated here, giving the scene depth through the air, blurring contours and outlines by means of less intense colours.</p><p>And as the German historian Carl Justi once put it: \"There is no painting that lets us forget this one.\"</p>";
    
    
