    NSString *goyaSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString *page81 = @"<p class=\"first\">Goya was educated as a Baroque painter living the transition into neoclassicism, but beyond that he signalled the beginning of modern painting. Painter and engraver, he never stopped learning and even being eighty years old he practiced lithography. In all his work, sometimes realist and other times surrealist, he imparted his personal vision, that ranged from the overflowing joy of paintings of popular festivities to the deepest pessimism of the war paintings, from fondness in portraits of the illustrious to irony in those of the royal family.</p><p>The birth of Goya occurred during a time of artistic and political Spanish colonialism. Since the death of Claudio Coello in 1693, Italian and French artists monopolized official institutions, the principal court commissions and public works. The ouvre of Goya didn't mean only new vigour and quality for Spanish painting, but also a universal opening to new techniques and, thus, the first steps towards what would become the new schools of Romanticism, Naturalism, and Impressionism that unfold during the 19th century are already seen by many in the life of the artist.</p><p>Until 1774 he spent years in education in the workshop of José Luzán, in Zaragoza, and in the shadow of his in-laws Francisco Bayeu (painter in the service of Charles III) and Ramón (disciple of the former). During these years he produces religious paintings linked to the late Baroque and to the Italian influences following his trip in 1770. In 1775 he is already in Madrid working for the Royal Tapestry Factory and opening his doors to Spanish nobility. In 1786 he was named court painter of Charles IV, which notably increases his dedication to portraiture. Years later, in 1793, he suffers an illness that leaves him completely deaf. In 1824, following the restoration of political absolutism, he voluntarily goes into exile in Bordeaux, France.</p><p>He died the 15th of April 1828 and was buried in the Chartreuse cemetery, in the Goicoechea family tomb. In 1900 his mortal remains were moved to the pantheon of the San Isidro cemetery in Madrid, where they remained until 1919, in which year they were transferred to their current resting place at the pantheon of St. Anthony of La Florida in Madrid.</p><p>Goya, who was a painter of women, a contemplator of mankind, a hardened hunter, lover of bullfights and the theatre, and of all kinds of local traditions (Romerias, verbenas, country excursions, bullfighting festivals, etc.), left an enormous artistic production (700 paintings, 280 etchings, more than 1000 drawings, mastering all the genres: religious painting, portraiture, costumbrismo, still lifes), that has its turning point in the severe illness he suffered in 1793, leaving him with a profound deafness and temporary paralysis in one arm. From that time on, Goya’s painting becomes more intimate and free, giving way without restrictions to his fantasies and to the search for new pictorial techniques. The process culminates in the Black Paintings that decorated the walls of the “Quinta del Sordo” (Deaf Man’s Villa) between 1820-1824. </p>";
    
    NSString *goyaSubtitle2 = @"Religious Painting";
    NSString *page821 = @"<p>During his formative years in Zaragoza and Italy Goya produces religious work tied to the late Baroque and to Italian and Neoclassical influences. The Neoclassicism is a rational art form developed at the end of the 18th century and the start of the 19th that expresses itself in the manner of Greco-Roman antiquity. The term ‘Neoclassicism’ was coined at the end of the 19th century to designate what was considered a lifeless and impersonal style, forgetting that it referred to an art form that sought perfection understood as harmony and permanence. It is the art of the Enlightenment and it expresses its desires for scientific progress and for a return to primitive simplicity. The themes chosen are from mythology and ancient history, giving them light and cold colours that transmit a message, a teaching, equilibrium, and restraint. Given the excesses of the Baroque and those of its final phase, Rococo, there is an attempt to return to the normalized and harmonious classicism of the Renaissance.</p>";
    NSString *page822 = @"<p>Neoclassicism and Romanticism share a common thread: they both turn their gaze back upon the past to recover elements of Greco-Roman or medieval antiquity. Their only difference is in the motives that drive them: rational ones, in the case of Neoclassicism, and sentimental or passionate ones in the case of Romanticism.</p><p>Using said Neoclassical technique, Goya depicted Saint Bernardine in order to win the favour of Charles III, as the painter aspired to be named court painter. It is considered one of the most accomplished religious works by Goya, who takes the opportunity to include his self-portrait in the face of the young man to the far right who looks at the viewer. Saint Bernardine (1380-1444), member of the noble family Albizzeschi, from Tuscany, was an influential character in Renaissance Italy. Preacher, Franciscan missionary, vicar, diplomat, and saint, he was canonized in 1450 by Pope Nicholas V. </p><p><br><br><br><br><br><br></p><p>The palette used in Pietà anticipates the colouring that Goya will use in his tapestry cartoons. Michelangelo's influence is evident in the composition of the scene and in the modelling of the robust and muscular body of Christ, as well as the treatment of the folds in the clothing that are more akin to sculpture than painting. On the other hand, the scene is balanced and full of restraint, conforming to the prevailing Neoclassicism. Nevertheless, the drama and religious intensity of other similar groups of the Baroque and Gothic are missing.</p><p><br><br><br><br><br><br><br></p><p>The miracle of Saint Anthony took place in the 18th century in Lisbon, Portugal. In that city Anthony's parents lived, while he at the time was in Padua, Italy. Once the news was heard of the accusation of assassination that was levelled against his father, an angel carried the saint to the city of Lisbon. The judge did not believe in the innocence of the father and Anthony attempted to interrogate the dead man, and a large crowd gathered to be present at the resurrection of the deceased and the exoneration of the accused. Goya moves the scene to 18th century Spain, inverting the traditional Baroque composition that placed cloud and glory with the angels in the cupola and the scene of the miracle in the lower part, painting the moment in which the saint performs the miracle in an utterly profane style. Together with the Black Paintings it is the prime expression of ‘goyan’ freedom. On the railing, several figures in different positions, postures, and richness of their features create a trompe l’oeil that make the railing appear to be architectural, making the third dimension sought since the times of Velázquez stand out. The later styles of Expressionism and Impressionism are already present here. The characters that surround the scene are folk from traditional Madrid, lower-class people known by Spanish terms such as </i>maja, chispero, embozado, or chulapa</i>.</p>";
    
    NSString *goyaSubtitle3 = @"Tapestry Cartoons";
    NSString *page831 = @"<p>Francisco Bayeu, Goya’s brother-in-law and director of the Royal Tapestry Factory, put forward the painter as a helper in said Factory designing models from 1774 to 1792; the themes, which were not of his choice but of the king Charles III and his children Charles and María Luisa, were popular and in the style of <i>costumbrismo</i>: pastoral, hunting, and rural. The cartoons, after having been transferred to tapestries, adorned rooms of palaces and royal sites, fitting well in the decoration of particular spaces.</p><p>This work, which to begin with brought him fame and money, later entailed a true tragedy for his spirit, as he continually struggled with iron moulds which restricted his creativity. The cartoons were fine sketches from which drawings could be copied. Looms are the most precise instrument for making tapestries, starting with a warp. This refers to a group of horizontally arranged parallel threads on which the cartoons scenes would be drawn. There are two different procedures: the first, the high warp loom, where the cartoon is placed behind the operator who uses a mirror to perform his work, and secondly, the low warp loom, which permits a greater speed as work is done on the obverse of the tapestry, though the resultant quality is lower. During this time seven series are catalogued, with varied themes, with a total of in between 60 and 73 works. The drawings had to be simple and the colours plain in order to be able to transfer them to wool; as Goya’s creativity shunned the required simplicity, the ire of the weavers increased due to the great difficulty of working with small figures forming great crowds, as in the case of The Meadow of San Isidro, until collaboration became impossible.</p>";
    NSString *page832 = @"<p>The Grape Harvest belongs to the group of paintings dedicated to depicting the four seasons of the year. Goya describes the cartoon with the words: “it shows a lady with her husband with a bunch of grapes in her hands and a boy in the process of taking them; behind them is a maidservant with a basket of grapes on her head.” There exists controversy over the characters shown here; according to historians like Ezquerra del Bayo the cartoon shows members of the House of Alba. There is no consensus regarding this hypothesis.</p><p>With regard to technique, delicate reds are dominant, applied delicately but firmly. The choice of a triangular composition is perfect for fixing the centre of attention on the characters in the foreground, at the same time leaving the landscape with grape pickers and the abrupt mountain at the background visible. Goya dedicated a series of cartoons to the representation of the four seasons. Another example is The Florists, representing spring with a group of women and children in the countryside, carrying flowers in their hands. Representing winter, Goya conceives a great snowfall over a deserted landscape, and for summer he creates a cartoon with scenes of the harvest and the gathering of wheat.</p>";
    
    NSString *goyaSubtitle4 = @"Caprichos";
    NSString *page841 = @"<p>Between 1793 and 1796, Goya created the series of eighty engravings that make up his <i>Caprichos</i>, “the author being persuaded that a critique of human errors and vices can also be the subject of painting.” Many of these engravings are clear precedents of what would become a booming genre during Romanticism: caricature. They make up a cruel satire of 18th century Spanish society, above all of its nobility and clergy. Well-connected among the learned, he shared his reflections on the defects of his society. They were against religious fanaticism, superstitions, the Inquisition, and some religious orders; they aspired to more just laws and a new educational system. All this he critiqued with humour and without mercy in these engravings. Knowing the risk involved, to protect himself he labelled some of his prints with ambiguous titles, especially the satires of the aristocracy and the clergy. Los Caprichos have influenced several generations of artists from such disparate movements as French Romanticism, Impressionism, German Expressionism, and Surrealism.</p><p>He distorted and exaggerated the physique of those that represented human vices and uglinesses, giving them bestial characteristics, perhaps trying to escape from the Inquisition’s intervention. In any case, everyone understood. He created them by etching and sold them for 12,000 Spanish <i>reales</i> as a life pension for his son Francisco Javier. The most common themes are: superstition about witches, the life and conduct of the clergy, eroticism, prostitution and madams, social satire of marriages of convenience, child-rearing and education, veiled criticisms of the Inquisition, etc.</p>";
    NSString   *page842 = @"<p>Goya used etching, which is a process by which the plate is completely protected by a varnish made of asphalt and beeswax that can be applied in a liquid or solid state and let dry. When dry, it is lifted using a punch or other utensil capable of removing varnish, following the drawing that one wishes to create and exposing the surface of the plate to the air. Once the varnish is lifted with the shape of the drawing, the metal plate is entered into a solution of water and acid, that corrodes the plate in the areas where the varnish has been removed and leaving a mark on the surface of the plate that is deeper the longer the plate has been exposed to the acid or the more concentrated the solution used is. The process reunites in one work of art the genius of the artist and the skill of the printer. Goya did both.</p><p><i>Se quebró el cántaro</i> (He broke the pitcher) is a devastating critique of the early education of infants, which did not exist as a state-regulated and protected institution. With the same philosophy that contains the infamous, in Spanish, phrase “la letra con sangre entra” (“the letter goes in with blood”, roughly equivalent to “spare the rod, spoil the child”), both actions, that of omission (not learning) and that of perpetration (breaking the pitcher), would unleash a beating that, at least here, the mother has the kindness to apply with the sole of her slipper. </p><p>Only the nobility and the upper classes had the possibility to educate their pupils using the ancient practice of hiring a tutor. Some charity institutions, essentially based in churches and convents, picked up children from the street and at the same time gave them some instruction in reading, writing, and arithmetic. </p>";
    
    NSString   *goyaSubtitle5 = @"The Peninsular War";
    NSString   *page851 = @"<p>By virtue of the Family Compacts between the French and Spanish Bourbons, Spain is allied with France who, at this time, is governed by Napoleon Bonaparte. In his war against England, Napoleon at first with permission and later de facto occupies the Iberian Peninsula with the intent of blockading the ports of the Portuguese, allies of England. Thus begins a long and cruel guerilla warfare campaign by the people organized in what were known as ‘Juntas de Defensa’ (Defence Boards).</p><p>The war revolved around three key factors: the clashing of normal armies, the sieges of Zaragoza, Gerona, and the conduct of the guerrillas. Spontaneity and heterogeneity were characteristics of the latter. They acted in the countryside, knowing the terrain to perfection, and they counted on popular support. They operated on the basis of surprise strikes, ambushes, and sabotage of enemy logistics and governance, and they never engaged in open battles. The military importance of the guerrilla in the conflict is undeniable as they collaborated with normal military units. Their leaders became very popular.</p><p>Parallel to the conflict the first attempt of bourgeois revolution in Spain took place. The Parliament of Cádiz convened and created the first Spanish constitution with a marked liberal bent, in 1812. Goya was very affected by the events of the war and for months afterwards documented in the series of etchings The Disasters of War all of the cruelty of the conflict.</p>";
    NSString *page852 = @"<p>The episode depicted in <i>The Charge of the Mamelukes</i> is the rebellion of the people of Madrid against the occupying French troops near to the Puerta del Sol. It is the first modern painting in the history of the medium: “a story without a hero”, its protagonists the anonymous people, that constitutes a real and bloody chronicle, far from mythological or legendary embellishments. It was painted years after the fact based on the testimonials of reliable witnesses; furthermore, it could be that one of these was Goya himself, as from the balcony of his house one could see the scenes of the conflict.</p>";
    NSString *page853 = @"<p>In The Third of May 1808, the event that Goya wants to memorialize is the drama that took place in Madrid starting on the morning of the second of may, after the attack of the populace on Murat’s cavalry while passing through the Puerta del Sol. Murat, Napoleon’s lieutenant, bathed Madrid in blood. The firing squads started against the walls of the Convent of Jesus in Buen Retiro, on the banks of the river, in the park of Casa de Campo, in Leganitos, in Santa Bárbara, in Puerta de Segovia, in Buen Suceso and on the Príncipe Pío mountain, lasting until four in the morning, the final moment chosen by Goya. A large lantern lights the scene. On one side is the perfect machinery of execution represented by the firing squad, and on the other is the patriot in white, offering his chest to the murderous bullets while crying out for love, liberty, and independence of the motherland. And in the center, the pool of blood.</p>";
    
    NSString *goyaSubtitle6 = @"Portraiture";
    NSString *page861 = @"<p>Goya took up the tradition of portraiture initiated by Claudio Coello and continued by other greats such as Velázquez, Carreño, and Vicente López. A large part of Goya’s work is made up of portraits, in which he was always subject to paradoxes or personal tensions, as he had to balance his own tastes with those of his sitters. In official portraits, he practiced a subtle criticism in the form of exaggerated compositions or an extraordinary and vulgar colouring, extending this critique even to the royal family. Nevertheless, commissions from friends or Enlightenment figures were painted with special affection, as were the portraits of anonymous people, people of the masses, depicted with sensibility and great realism.</p>";
    NSString *page862 = @"<p>Very little is known for sure about these celebrated paintings. Manuel Godoy kept all the paintings of the House of Alba after the mysterious death of the duchess in 1802. After the fall of the prime minister in 1808 the paintings were considered obscene and they were deposited with the Presidency of the Council. In 1814 the Inquisition intervenes, denouncing Goya who is asked to testify. In 1845 Viardot’s book The Museums of Spain is published, where it is said that the woman in the paintings is the Duchess of Alba, which has been debated by anthropologists and historians.</p><p>The academic Ezquerra de Bayo writes that “the two majas, nude and clothed, having the same proportions, were created in such a way that one would cover the other, letting the nude appear through an ingenious mechanism.” The Spanish concept maja could be compared to the French “femme fatale”. Rivers of ink have been spent in expounding on the torrid and unstable relationship between the painter and the duchess. Critics, specialists, and historians even deny it. Nevertheless, other paintings by Goya come close to confirming it; in one of them the duchess appears dressed in a black dress and mantilla, with her right index finger pointing at a small sign on the floor on which is written “Solo Goya”, which can be translated as “Only Goya” or “Goya alone”. In another, dishevelled and coquettish, Goya laments the inconstancy and fickleness of female love.</p>";
    NSString *page863 = @"<p>This work marks the apogee of Goya’s official career as court painter of Charles IV. The studies of the main characters are made separately in the Palace of Aranjuez. The king and queen, the infantes María Josefa and Antonio (siblings of the king), Carlos María Isidro, Ferdinand, María Isabel, Francisco and María Luisa (the king’s children) and a few others appear in it.</p><p>In the work, one can infer the stress of the author and his effort to reconcile his service to the royal family and the indifference and coldness that it inspired in him; the composition, the people depicted in the painting and their expressions are a far cry away from the affable and intimate atmosphere that Velázquez attained with his meninas. For example: the queen María Luisa was in reality ugly, and he painted her thus, though Goya, who was not thoughtless, compensated her by showing off the long, shapely, and beautiful arms that she really did possess. Goya, in the manner of Velázquez in his magnum opus, paints his veiled self-portrait. The painter infuses the group with a degenerate air, as if foreshadowing the sad events that would soon take place: the defeat of the Armada at Trafalgar (1805), the Mutiny of Aranjuez (1808), the Abdications of Bayonne (1808), and the Peninsular War (1808-1814). Of everyone present, the male children of the king, Ferdinand and Carlos María Isidro, were the protagonists of a painful development of 19th century Spain. After the Peninsular War, Ferdinand VII (reigned 1814-1833) was crowned as king and the first thing he did was to abolish the constitution of 1812. In 1820, a military coup led by Riego forced him to reinstate it, giving way to the <i>Trienio Liberal</i> (Liberal Triennium). Following this parenthesis, the monarchies of Europe united in the Holy Alliance sent an army in his aid (the Hundred Thousand Children of Saint Louis) that let him return to absolutism during the next ten years (the Ominous Decade), until his death in 1833. This political and social instability, in the end, brought the country to ruin after the ravages of war.</p>";
    
    NSString *goyaSubtitle7 = @"Black Paintings";
    NSString *page871 = @"<p>Goya decorated the rooms of the house he had bought, called La Quinta del Sordo (the Deaf Man’s Villa), between 1820 and 1822. He did it with absolute liberty and with a palette knife in lieu of a brush, achieving an effect that is admirable at a certain distance. Regarding their significance, all is conjecture.</p><p>As an example, the palette used by Goya in <i>Two Old Men Eating Soup</i> includes ochres, grays, blacks, earthen and golden colours, with a white here and there in the clothing or green in the sparse landscape. The theme, composition, and colour make these paintings a clear precedent of Expressionism. They are 14 oil paintings painted on walls whitewashed with plaster. The brushstrokes are loose and violent, seemingly depicting visions of strange significance, in which are interlaced religious and profane themes. It is possible that they are not works born of chance or taste, but rather that they conceal some sort of symbolism, into which is mixed the feelings of loneliness, melancholy, sickness and death that surrounded the painter.</p>";
    
    NSString *goyaSubtitle8 = @"Goya’s Exile";
    NSString *page881 = @"<p>In 1824, after the restoration of absolutism and the repeal of the constitution of 1812, Goya left for France. He went disgusted and perplexed by the sad reality of Spain, loyal to the idea that inside every honest Spaniard resides an exile. A young widow, Leocadia Weiss, and her two children Rosarito and Guillermo accompany him.</p><p>Goya is at this time 81 years old and his physical decrepity is not in line with his intellectual and creative vigour. In Bordeaux, escaping as much from the Spanish court that asphyxiates him as from his own terrors and loneliness, he continues his artistic production, innovating and searching ceaselessly other modes of expression. He was still able to complete two masterpieces, the portrait of Juan Muguiro and the famous <i>The Milkmaid of Bordeaux</i>.</p><p>The latter was completed a year prior to his death. In the work, one can barely see the outlines, the volume is achieved through layering of paint and the colours are in abundance, applied in long and fine brushstrokes. Romanticism is already making its way through Europe and Goya, who was the first to cultivate it, adheres to this exalted and passionate sentiment and produces his last work inspired by the popular nineteenth-century French milkmaids.</p>";
    
