    NSString *romanSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString *page91 = @"<p class=\"first\"><p>Romanticism encompasses a collection of intellectual movements emerging as a reaction against the Neoclassicism of the previous century that, at the end of the 18th century, made emotions prevail over reason. As general characteristics we can pinpoint the preponderance of imagination over critical analysis, the free expression of sensations, individualism, and finally, the taste for mystery, exoticism - especially when expressed through Orientalist themes - and the past, as for example in a resurrection of the Middle Ages. Finally, we can observe an encouragement of nationalist sentiment and patriotic exaltation.</p><p>The Romantic movement affected every part of society: in the political sphere various liberal and democratic revolutions stand out; in the social, unionist struggle in favour of the working classes is born; in regards to the treatment of nature, a certain anxiety in the face of its uncontrollable force is experienced, and finally, Romanticism also emerges in the religious sphere, in the form of a profound experience that will drive the missionary movement.</p><p>In conclusion, and to paraphrase Victor Hugo: “A double goal, freedom in art and freedom in society.”</p><p>Romanticism arrives late to Spain, primarily due to the historical events that occur. Francisco de Goya, with the Peninsular War in his sight, is the first and greatest Romantic. Hs work anticipates in several ways the new movement. Other generations of painters succeed him who in many cases mix and combine different influences giving rise to a style named Eclecticism.</p>";
    
    NSString *romanSubtitle2 = @"Romantic Portraiture";
    NSString *page921 = @"<p>Two important painters worked on Romantic portraiture: Federico Madrazo Kuntz and Antonio María Esquivel. Federico Madrazo Kuntz (1815-1894) comes from an interesting lineage of painters: son of the famous painter José Madrazo and son-in-law of a Polish painter, his daughter Cecilia married another noted painter, Mariano Fortuny. Kutz was the portraitist par excellence of the aristocracy of his time and also director of the Museo del Prado, the Academy of Fine Arts of San Fernando and court painter to Isabelle II. In his Parisian stay he perfected next to Ingres the techniques of portraiture.</p>";
    NSString   *page922 = @"<p>Once his quality as a portraitist was proven, the aristocracy calls on his services in spite of the high fees he demanded. His portrait of the Countess of Vilches combines the aristocratic demeanour of the model, despite her informal pose, with the kindness that radiates from her face. The purity of the outlines, the pinkish whiteness of her body and the exquisite detailing of her clothing, not forgetting the brilliant colouring, make this work a model of Romantic portraiture. Amalia is 20 years old at the time of having her portrait painted, and she presents to us her full length, wearing an elegant blue gauze dress, with a tulle adorned with blue satin, with a wide neckline and a tight-fitting waist. The light slides along the length of her skirt, increasing the brightness of the whites of the bodice that are contrasted with the electric blue of the adornments. The critic Antoni de Marichalar affirms being in the presence of “our Gioconda of the 19th century due to her fixed gaze directed towards the viewer with coquetry and her half, promising smile.”</p>";
    NSString   *page923 = @"<p>Antonio María Esquivel (1806-1857) was born in Seville and studied in the Academy of Fine Arts of the city, where he became familiarized with Murillo’s techniques. In 1831 he moves to Madrid, entering the Academy of Fine Arts of San Fernando where he occupied the chair of Pictorial Anatomy. Threatened by blindness, a tragedy without equal for any painter, he attempted suicide in the waters of the Guadalquivir. During his stay in Madrid he became integrated into the artistic exhibitions that were held in the rich mansions of the aristocracy and bourgeoisie and which were attended by politicians, authors, musicians, painters, and “Romantics in general”.</p><p>Affected by the illness that threatened to leave him blind, intellectuals and friends from the Academy, after a collection, aided in a long and expensive treatment with very satisfactory results. As a way of saying thanks, the painter made this collective portrait of his benefactors, constituting a gallery of distinguished people from Romantic society of his time. The perfection in the drawing, above and beyond the colouring, justifies his chair of Pictorial Anatomy.</p>";
    
    NSString   *romanSubtitle3 = @"Landscape";
    NSString   *page931 = @"<p>The most celebrated spanish romantic painter of landscapes is Genaro Pérez Villaamil (1.807-1.854). Along with David Roberts, a british painter, he travelled through Spain looking for pintoresque lanscapes and scenes that would conform the book \"Artistic and monumental Spain\".</p><p>Villaamil received powerful influences from English landscape painting from Roberts and Turner. His technique is full of impasto, nervous and with a warm and bright colour, with dreamy and mysterious atmospheres. He peoples his paintings with a great number of small figures, exotic and with Oriental flavour.</p><p>With regards to his creative process, Villaamil took notes and drew sketches of nature that, later on in his studio, transformed into daydreams or fantasy. He peoples his paintings with a great number of small figures that he distributes without any established order.</p>";
    
    
    NSString   *romanSubtitle4 = @"Costumbrismo";
    NSString   *page941 = @"<p>Leonardo Alenza (1807-1845), like a good Romantic, had a sensitive, introverted, and sickly nature. He studied in the Academy of San Fernando with Neoclassical teachers and ambience. A good number of specialists in Romanticism consider Alenza (together with Lucas) the creator of Madridian Costumbrismo despite his Neoclassical training. He left a multitude of small format paintings in which he paints nimble and lively scenes from folklife and suburban life in Madrid, gifted with loose brushstrokes and a great chromatic richness.</p><p>In this scene we see a landscape framed by public architecture, creating a space in which to place the circle of figures that attentively listen to the adventures of the protagonist. The intense expressivity of the audience stands out. Everyday society in Madrid is reflected in these works that, in general, arise from a purely descriptive spirit, with neither complaint nor critique. One can see influences from Goya in the application of the patches of colour, relegating the precision of the sketching and the study of light.</p><p>";
    
    
    NSString   *romanSubtitle5 = @"Historical Painting";
    NSString   *page951 = @"<p>The Historical painting in the context of Spanish Romanticism covers a prolific production of paintings that occurred in Spanish painting in the second half of the 19th century as a consequence of the historicism supported by official means, through the juicy prizes in the recently created Nacional Exhibitions. Great events of the past are painted, intending to present with realism events of the national historic past, a retrospective realism.</p>";
    NSString   *page952 = @"<p>Antonio Gisbert Pérez, ideologically liberal, was always a militant in progressive parties, becoming an icon for his fellow believers. The comuneros Padilla, Bravo, and Maldonado, representatives from the community in Castilian cities, rose up in arms in defence of the old laws and customs of the kingdom against the imperialistic designs of the monarch Charles I, named Holy Roman Emperor. The comuneros were defeated in Villalar in 1521 and sentenced to death by decapitation. The scene recreates said execution.</p><p>The gallows, raised above the eyes of the viewer, gains depth with the presence, in the top right corner, of the country house and church of the town. Francisco Padilla, in the centre and dressed in rich clothing, listens to the friar who is pointing to the sky, while he, resigned and without fear, watches the corpse of Juan Bravo. Francisco Maldonado climbs up to the platform, tired of the other friar’s admonitions. Padilla being the centre figure, the event is balanced and in sequence: ascension to the platform, the wait, beheading. The painting was meant to be seen from below, giving the viewer the sensation that he or she is standing under the gallows. </p><p>Several elements of <i>The Legend of the Monk King</i> by José Casado Alisal contribute to emphasisaing the tragic and dramatic nature of the painting: the icy cold atmosphere of the dungeon, the ferocious and threatening mastiff that the king barely manages to hold back, the rushing and worried crowd of courtiers that struggle to enter the room, their expressions going from anger to vengeance through fear, condemnation, or rage, the spectral light whose source is not visible, the empty central space of the scene, and, of course, the decapitated heads.<p></p> Ramiro II, called the Monk, king of Aragon, discovered in time a conspiracy against his rule headed by the archbishop Pedro de Lucría. His punishment did not delay. He ordered the beheading of all the conspirators. He arranged their heads, once cut off, in a circular, bell-shaped pattern and hung from the ceiling in the centre the head of the archbishop, as if it were that bell’s clapper.<p><i>Queen Isabel la Católica Dictating her Last Will and Testament</i> by Eduardo Rosales is considered the finest work of Spanish historical painting. Times are bad and recourse is made to imperial nostalgia in order to cover the widespread decay of the kingdom. In the painting we see Queen Isabella I in the midst of dictating her last will and testament on the 12th of October 1504, in the castle of Medina del Campo where she died of cancer on the 26th of November the same year.</p><p> The queen is lying on a bed with a large canopy bearing the coat of arms of Castille, among cushions and wearing a transparent veil. In front of her the scribe at his writing desk labours at his writing. To her left, sitting down and his feet resting on a black velvet cushion is her husband Ferdinand of Aragon with a distant and dejected air. At the foot of the bed are Cardinal Cisneros and the Marquesses of Moya, loyal vassals and servants. The light that illuminates the scene creates a dense and excessive atmosphere, fitting for a dying person’s bedroom.<p></p> The painting meant the rediscovery of Baroque and of its great masters like Velázques, Murillo, and Zurbarán. The characters express their feelings: Ferdinand, her husband, dejection and responsibility, Cardinal Cisneros’ profile reveals his astute and wise character, the marquesses show fidelity and affection, blurred by the Velázquean air that envelops the scene. The brushstrokes reaffirm the quality, texture, and weight of the clothes, especially those of the overcoat of the courtier in the foreground.</p><p><i>Lucretia</i>, Roman native, was raped by the son of the last king of Rome, Tarquinius, precipitating the establishment of the Republic. In 510 B.C.E. Lucretia committed suicide to cleanse the dishonour that had befallen her father Lucretius and her husband Collatinus. Both hold her in their arms while Brutus pulls out the dagger with which the lady stabbed herself in the heart, exclaiming: “By this blood most pure I swear that the outrage wrought by the king's son will receive its due punishment.” Lucretia became in this way the example of moral valour before dishonour and attacks against family.</p><p>The dramatic and simple scene takes place in a simple room without any more furnishing than a solitary bronze statue. The novelty is in the application of a broad and quick brushstroke with which Rosales models figures and clothing, reinforcing their volume thanks to the sketching and chiaroscuro. The colour is limited, using cold tones that elevate the drama of the subject. It is interesting to pay attention to the beauty of the characters’ poses, as if they were all performing a ballet step. In 1882 the state purchased the canvas from Rosales’ widow for 35,000 pesetas. </p></p>";
    
    
    NSString   *romanSubtitle6 = @"Social Realism";
    NSString   *page961 = @"<p>Towards the central decades of the 19th century Romanticism started giving way to Realism. Various factors contribute to the change. First of all, the weight and terrible consequences of the Industrial Revolution start to loom in peoples’ consciences (children and women working, long hours, grievous living conditions, unsanitary housing, the lack of any kind of protection against disease and unemployment, etc.) Secondly, the revolutionary failures of 1848 and the loss of all trace of idealism were other determining factors. Consequently, social themes become frequent and artists tend to depict men and women performing simple everyday tasks. Fatigue, work, and effort are principal subjects.</p>";
    NSString   *page962 = @"<p>Joaquin Sorolla (1863-1923) was a prolific Valencian painter with more than 2200 catalogued works. He was orphaned at the age of two and once his formative period had ended, he started sending works to every exhibition announced. In <i>Trafficking Human Beings</i> Sorolla approaches the subject of prostitution with discretion and clemency. A group of women dressed in rural garb with mantillas and scarves appear to nap, with the exception of the old woman who stays awake and alert. The narrow cubicle that encloses them appears to symbolize the impossibility of escaping their fate. The painting was highly criticized by the most reactionary sectors of Spanish Catholicism.</p><p>This work recounts a passage from the novel <i>Flor de Mayo</i> (Mayflower) by Vicente Blasco Ibáñez, taking place on the beaches of the El Cabañal neighbourhood of Valencia. In said novel a fisherman dies and the aunt of the deceased, between weeping and sorrow, exclaims “they still say that fish is expensive!” Two fishermen attend to a dying, naked third wearing a medallion around his neck, which could very well bear the image of Our Lady of Mount Carmel, protector of sea-faring men. Around them are objects of common use and presence in fishermen’s boats: an oil lamp, a barrel, ropes, and fish.</p>";
    
