    NSString *veinteSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString *page101 = @"<p class=\"first\">The hundred years that passed from the end of the 19th century to the end of the 20th is characterized by its shaping of multiple currents that are not always chronologically linear; instead, many are coexistent and interrelated. It is the century of ‘isms’: Impressionism, Post-Impressionism, Modernism, etc.<p></p>With regards to Spain, the years between the defeat of ‘98 and the start of the Civil War in 1936 were some of the most decisive decades of the country’s modern history. The Spanish-American War and the resulting Treaty of Paris of 1898 meant the loss of Cuba, Puerto Rico, and the Philippines, the last territories of that vast empire on which “the sun never set”. The deep mark left by the event was spread throughout the nation in the form of pessimism and hopelessness that, necessarily, influenced culture and intellectuals of its time. But the reaction was immediate, and with the name The ‘98 Generation one generally means a group of writers and thinkers whose common concern was to capture the essence of Spanishness, the exaltation of Castile, and political, social, and economic regeneration.<p></p>The pessimistic mark is reflected at first in art and literature: Sorolla, Zuloaga, Unamuno, Azorín and others searched for the significance of the Spanish in relation to the rest of Europe. A new wave of thinkers and artists made up the so-named ‘27 Generation. Poets such as García Lorca, Gerardo Diego, or Rafael Alberti made an effort to recover national self-esteem, re-reading classics and remembering folk traditions and regional folklore. This cultural ardour was brought to an abrupt halt by a new and disastrous conflict between Spaniards of different ideologies: the Civil War of 1936-1939.<p></p>The year 1863 can be chosen as the starting date of modern painting. It is the year in which Manet paints Le déjeuner sur l’herbe, exhibited in the ‘Salón de los Rechazados’ (a group of painters excluded from the official exhibition circuit due to the avant-garde nature of their work). Impressionism and later Post-Impressionism constitute the starting point for the currents of the 20th century.</p>";
    
    NSString *veinteSubtitle2 = @"Late Impressionism";
    NSString *page1021 = @"<p>Impressionism first emerged in France in the last third of the 19th century. It tends not to reproduce reality, but rather to subtly reflect the impression that it leaves in the soul of the painter. The Impressionists wanted to synthesise the simultaneous effects of light, space, and colour into a single sensory impression. Inspired by physical theories about the composition of light, pure Impressionism limits its palette to colours of the solar spectrum, from whose contrast it obtains its effects of light. Manet, Monet, Sisley, Renoir, Degas, and Pissarro are the most important painters of the movement.</p><p>The Impressionist movement arrived late to Spain, practically at the end of the century, although Goya in his genius anticipated its beginnings. To illustrate late Spanish Impressionism, we will make reference to an old acquaintance, Joaquín Sorolla, who after some social Realism paintings (Trafficking in Human Beings) and some historical paintings (The Defence of the Monteleón Artillery Barracks) made contact with the European avant-garde at the start of the 20th century, approaching Impressionism with which he was already familiar following his trip to Paris in 1885. He developed a pictorial style called Luminism. He started to paint outdoors, mastering the use of light and combining it with quotidian and landscape scenes from the Mediterranean life that he grew up in.</p>";
    NSString   *page1022 = @"<p>The eastern Spanish beach scenes and the Impressionist effects of reverberating light are characteristic of Sorolla’s art, managing to communicate the splendour and laziness of a beach morning, with a vibrant colouring and a loose and vigorous style.</p><p><i>The Fisherman</i> was painted on the Valencian beach of El Cabañal and shows the figure of a boy transporting the day’s catch in a basket. The luminosity of the ensemble stands out, in which pink and blue tones are predominant. The boy appears diagonally, with the figure cut off above the knees, with a bare torso and a hat to protect from the sun. In a basket he carries the day’s catch, half-covered by a wind-whipped cloth. There is talk of a certain influence from photography; not in vain, as Sorolla married Clotilde, daughter of a photographer in whose studio he worked as a young man.</p>";
    NSString   *page1023 = @"<p>In <i>Walk on the Beach</i> Clotilde García, holding a parasol and together with her eldest daughter María Clotilde, walks along the Valencian beach at dusk while the sea breeze ripple their clothes. The loose brushstrokes, the light, the colour, and the movement that the painting transmit explain the enormous success it has enjoyed.</p>";
    
    NSString   *veinteSubtitle3 = @"Modernism";
    NSString   *page1031 = @"<p>Modernism was an artistic style that was successful at the end of the 19th and start of the 20th century, characterized by a combination of neo-mediaeval memories, Romantic remains, and Baroque elements. Though soon surpassed, it produced some masterpieces and opened the way for 20th century art. In Spain this trend was centered in Catalunya and was expressed mainly in architecture through the works of Gaudí. In regards to painting, Ramón Casas and Ignacio Zuloaga stand out.</p><p>Ramón Casas (1866-1932) leads the group of artists and intellectuals who meet in the Barcelona bar ‘Els Quatre Gats’. Ramón Casas was made famous by his portraits, caricatures, and paintings of the social, intellectual, economic, and political elite of Barcelona, Madrid, and Paris. He was a graphic designer and his postcards and posters contribute to developing Catalan Modernism. Coming from a wealthy family, Casas lived for long periods of time in Paris, alternating with Barcelona and the rest of Spain. In 1906 he met Julia Peraire, lottery saleswoman, and painted her portrait at the age of 18. Soon she became his model and lover, and they eventually married with the disapproval of his family.</p>";
    NSString   *page1032 = @"<p>Cafés are one of the favourite motifs of the paintings carried out in Paris at the turn of the century, revolving around scandalous themes that recreate atmospheres with little to recommend them. A lone woman in a café, drinking and smoking, was an unequivocal image for the conservative public of the time. The model used in this painting was Madeleine de Boisguillaume, who also modelled for Toulouse-Lautrec, and as such the painting is also known as La Madeleine. Casas shows his influence from Manet and his painting of the bar at the Foliès-Bergere. The scene is painted in a single foreground plane, with the mirror allowing the viewer to see the salon and guess that the woman is sitting in the far corner.</p><p><b>Ignacio Zuloaga</b> (1870-1945) received his formation in the Museo del Prado copying works by Ribera, Velázquez, Goya, and El Greco. He moves to Rome and Paris where he lives with and gets to know the avant-garde of the century. Together with his uncle he settles in Segovia, searching for the roots of Spain in Castilian austerities, becoming interested in the landscapes of Castile and its humble people, using dark tones that link in with the idea of deep and dark Spain. The trail of El Greco, Velázquez, and Goya remains throughout his life, and he proves himself an excellent landscapist and a masterful portraitist of the ladies of high society, bullfighters, prostitutes, and people of low social standing.</p><p>The Countess of Noailles, poet and model used by various painters at the start of the century, was painted by Zuloaga in this splendid work. She appears reclined on a divan covered by green cloth (calling to mind Goya’s maja), directing her intense gaze at the viewer and dressed in a vaporous white gown, shoes, and black tights. The composition is organized by the horizontal line of the divan, set against the vertical lines of the curtains and the curves of the countess, whose erect head reinforces the verticality of the composition. Zuloaga uses gaudy and soft colours at the same time, with influences from Fauvism (a very colourful style epitomized by Matisse), though the weight of the Spanish Baroque and Goya is felt.</p>";
    NSString   *page1033 = @"<p>Maurce Barres era un hispanista aficionado a la historia y a las tradiciones, interesándose especialmente por el pasado de Toledo. Cuando Zuloaga lo retrató emplea una composición protagonizada al mismo tiempo  por el escritor y la ciudad imperial, tomando como referencia  la vista y plano de Toledo que tomó El Greco; el hijo de éste, Jorge Manuel, posa en la zona derecha de la composición; en la obra de Zuloaga, el protagonista se sitúa a la izquierda, pero el resultado final es igual de espectacular. El puente, el alcázar, la catedral y el tajo del río, prestan a la obra una notable monumentalidad. Los tonos tan oscuros y la escasa luz espectral que no se sabe de donde viene, conecta esta obra con momentos del manierismo de El Greco.</p>";
    
    
