    NSString   *picassoSubtitle1 = @"Introducción";
    NSString   *page111 = @"<p class=\"first\">Picasso is one of the most relevant artists in the history of Spanish painting. He lived to be nearly ninety-three, a considerable record of longevity, and what is more, his strength never seemed to fail him, which he nevertheless generously squandered at the altar of an intensely passionate temperament and an iron will at his work. This torrent of vitality being very notable, what was exceptional in him was not only these extraordinary physical characteristics that nature had bestowed upon him, but the vigor of his artistic talent, in which it is difficult to find a rival in the capacity to create, from beginning to end, without faltering. Picasso was the artist of a thousand styles and manners, experimenting with all kinds of techniques, who never tired in starting from scratch.</p><p>Málaga was his city of birth; A Coruña and Barcelona, due to his father’s profession, professor of Drawing and Fine Arts, saw him grow up and develop his artistic precocity. In 1895 he entered the Catalan avant-garde that frequented ‘Els Quatre Gats’ (The four cats) in Barcelona and in 1904 he settled in Paris, not forever, as he frequently travelled to Madrid or Barcelona and, above all, spent long holidays in Cadaqués, Girona, Spain. In 1960, Picasso moves for good to Nôtre-Dame-de-Vie in Mougins, where he spent his last years.</p>";
    
    NSString   *picassoSubtitle2 = @"Rose and Blue Periods";
    NSString   *page1121 = @"<p>Picasso’s Expressionist period from 1900 to 1907 is subdivided into the Rose and Blue Periods.</p><p>In “The Artist's Sister Lola”, Picasso’s sister poses seated, very naturally, on a couch. The blues of her clothes and the red of the chair seat stand out for their brightness on a subdued background made up of different ochre tones. Her hands, even though completely lacking accuracy, possess a great force of expression: one open, as a prolongation of her arm rested on the couch, the other, closed and relaxed on her skirt. With this work, Picasso abandons for good the academic canons of his first education sponsored by his father the Fine Arts professor. In this period his drawing pads are full of hundreds of sketches, including an immense variety of street scenes, bullfights, landscapes, and portraits of friends and family (Picasso is at this time 18).</p>";
    NSString   *page1122 = @"<p>A dense and dramatic blue plays a crucial part in this work, though the static and worn out figure of the old man, immersed in a depressive and oppressive atmosphere, is imbued with an immense and destructive power. He seems to search for the last breath of his defeated spirit. Picasso was accused of facile sentimentalities in some of his works from the blue period, but his technique, the plaintive observation of reality and the psychological study of the character, save the painter from a simple and ordinary social chronicle. The elongated limbs, the shape of his hands, the foreshortening of the figure, and the affected gestures are reminiscent of El Greco’s Mannerist style, but at the same time, the geometric shape of the figure, constructed around the central axis of the guitar, heralds the composition of the still lifes of his future Cubist period.This Expressionist blue period is characterized not only be the use of this color, but also by the bitterness that he draws in his desolate figures, principally women, in postures of misery and helplessness. They are years of material hardship for Picasso, living together with other bohemians in a miserable hut in Montmartre, the Parisian artists’ neighborhood, called Bateau-Lavoir.</p>";
    NSString   *page1123 = @"<p>“Family of Acrobats (or Jugglers)” is the largest work painted up until this moment by Picasso. It looks like a reunion with his friends from the circus under a blue sky and against an insignificant landscape. Previously, Picasso had made frequent studies of different circus performers separately: lion tamers, trapeze artists, tightrope walkers, and clowns. Here he seems to have reunited them all. The desolation and anguish of earlier works seems to have disappeared and the group of acrobats appear relaxed and comfortable in their work. Nevertheless, rose and blue, colours that we find in combination in other works of his rose period, constitute a unifying element and give the group a melancholy air. The rose period is distinguished by its pastel colours and warm tones, by its soft and delicate lines and by the elongated sketching of figures in El Greco’s Mannerist style.</p>";
    
    NSString   *picassoSubtitle3 = @"Cubism";
    NSString   *page1131 = @"<p>Cubism was an artistic, and especially pictorial, revolution, headed by Picasso, Braque, Juan Gris, and Leger. The name was originally a term of derision coined by Matisse, but nevertheless, it was adapted. Three Cubist periods can be distinguished. The movement started giving structure to the forms disintegrated by Cézanne’s late Impressionism, the so-named Cézannian Cubism; later these forms were reduced to pure geometry and, to give an example, a head is equivalent to a sphere, in the so-named Analytic Cubism; later still, Cubism synthesised more or less arbitrary works with what could be cutouts from the geometrical world, difficult to recognise but of a great decorative value. This is known as Synthetic Cubism. Finally, there were remains of its principles in works that evolved towards Futurism, abstraction or figurative art: Organic Cubism.</p>";
    NSString   *page1132 = @"<p>Not even his close friends, Matisse and Braque, understood the reach of this groundbreaking work. Nevertheless, Cézanne’s important retrospective exhibition in 1907 was decisive for Picasso, who was searching for the geometry of structure and reproduction of volume. Cézanne reduces objects to primary volumes, generally curves: sphere, cone, cylinder, while Picasso and Braque prefer those with rectilinear edges: cubes, pyramids, parallelepipeds. Thus was Analytic Cubism created.</p><p>After a lot of sketching and drawing work, in few days Picasso painted this nearly 6 metres squared painting. The flesh tones of the five female nudes are bright against the blue curtain in the background accentuating the sensuality of the scene, nevertheless the sustained and penetrating gaze of the group of hieratic women disarm and disquiet the viewer. There is no movement in the group, instead a static and exhibitionist pose that makes the audience uneasy. The deformed faces of the women on the right are reminiscent of African primitive art, which had interested Picasso for a period.</p><p>Picasso logra el volumen no a base de perspectiva o degradación cromática, sino aplicando un dibujo firme y unas líneas sólidas a una concepción geométrica del cuerpo humano</p>";
    NSString   *page1133 = @"<p>The face, figure, and clothes of the sitter are covered by small brushstrokes that are reminiscent of the knots of a wooden table, creating soft effects of light and shadow. The woman is simplified into a blocky whole, practically featureless and without detail in her hands. The mandolin shows the same technique: a geometric block with a firm line here or there to add volume. The unity of the composition, woman plus mandolin, is thus assured. The style, very simplified, of lines and spots of color, of the woman and the objects that surround her, transmit to the viewer pleasant sensations of closeness, peace, and musicality.</p>";
    NSString   *page1134 = @"<p>Here is Synthetic Cubism. The work is painted from various points of view and the principles of realist representation of space are abandoned. The bottle and glass have been divided into numerous small surfaces, giving way to complicated effects of light and shade and making the unity of the contours and volume disappear. Both the bottle and the glass look like a plain colour print, however, the remaining forms of the composition - the window, signs, and the surface of the table - evoke the atmosphere of a small, cozy, and pleasant café, whose charm does not escape Picasso’s eye. On other occasions, the painter captures the colourfulness of a striking tapestry and paints it with an intense colour background, discovering a new, extremely decorative technique: Pointillism.</p>";
    
    NSString   *picassoSubtitle4 = @"Classicism";
    NSString   *page1141 = @"<p>Maternity is the most important subject that Picasso explores in the year his son Pablo was born. The mother of little Pablo was Olga Khokhlova, dancer in the Russian ballet directed by Sergei Diaghilev for which Picasso designed costumes and sets based on movable Cubist forms that received the audience’s applause.</p>";
    NSString   *page1142 = @"<p>In the composition of La Maternité one can see a new side of Picasso’s multifaceted art: the monumental figure of the mother, with a plump body, strong hands, heavy feet, sitting on the sand, bows her head towards the naked child with a look of satisfaction, affection, and serenity. The simplification of the figures, their ‘stony’ character and soft forms, are an exuberant representation of human life.<br><br></p><p>In Three Women at a Fountain, a composition of ample dimensions and Neoclassicist style, three monumental female figures, enveloped in tunics with firm folds, watch each other with such intense stares that they appear to pierce each other. The rhythm of the composition revolves around the splendid set of three hands in the centre, while the other three, further apart, make up a perfect triangle. The fleshy, solid bodies, the strong and powerful hands, and the feet firmly planted on the ground produce an architectural or sculptural impression, reinforced by the folds of the tunics that look like the grooves of columns. The set of colours is very restrained: over the terracotta of the bodies, against a dark background, the marble white of their clothes stands out.</p><p>In The Lovers there can be seen a great purity in the classical lines and sculptural solidity in the bodies. In these two figures that are united in the young man’s embrace the purity of the classical lines of the faces and the veil that softly covers her head and right arm exists side by side with the sculptural solidity of the bodies and the rest of the clothing. Their hands also possess the robustness of the monumental nudes from two years previous, in contrast with the stylized and light lines that the faces are drawn with. The colors are magnifically harmonious, forming a palette of romantic colors without ever succumbing to sentimentality.</p>";
    
    NSString   *picassoSubtitle5 = @"Surrealism";
    NSString   *page1151 = @"<p>When on the 30th of April 1937 the news arrives to Paris that the small city of Guernica had been bombed in the middle of the day, with the streets full of people, Picasso, enraged, already knew what the subject of the work that the government of the Spanish Republic had commissioned for its pavillion at the World Fair would be.</p>";
    NSString   *page1152 = @"<p>The first thing we see is the atrocity of war: the dead child, the house in flames, mangled bodies, cries of agony, and astonished looks. The sun’s disc has contracted into an oval shape reminiscent of a pupil-less eye and in its centre is a light bulb, as if the source of natural light, ashamed, refuses to light the Dantesque scene. Nevertheless, in the window a woman firmly holds a candle, clearly recording the scene so that future generations do not forget the ravages of war. The bull watches the scene disconcertedly. The warrior lies below the horse’s hooves, tightly clutching his broken sword; to balance these dramatic actions, a bird on a table in the background flaps its wings and cries out to the sky. The horse fixes the viewer’s attention; with its open mouth, taking its final breath, it takes a rebellious last stand of resistance. The most moving figures are the four women, whose postures and expressions convey astonishment, fear, and overwhelming pain.</p><p>The discoveries of Cubism, the purity of lines of the Neoclassical period, and the unbridled distortions of the preceding period’s nudes unite to allow Picasso to create this monument to human desperation.</p>";
    
    NSString   *picassoSubtitle6 = @"Postwar";
    NSString   *page1161 = @"<p>Regretfully, Picasso was a suffering witness to the convulsed and bellicose 20th century: the 1st and 2nd World Wars, the Spanish Civil War of 1936-1939, the Korean, Algerian, Vietnam, and Cold Wars, the assassination of Kennedy in Dallas and many other conflicts. Throughout all of them, Picasso stood on the side of the humble victims, calling out for peace and happiness of human beings. What is more, he forbade that his work Guernica, property of the Spanish state, return to Spain as long as there was not a democratically elected government in power. His efforts were not in vain, as his drawing of a dove with a laurel in its beak has become a universal symbol of pacifism.</p>";
    NSString   *page1162 = @"<p>At the behest of the council of Vallauris, Picasso decorates a 12th century chapel with the works War and Peace. In War, fire-breathing demons who burn and throw insects around them symbolize of the horrors of war. In the centre of Peace, Pegasus, the winged horse of Greek mythology, pulls a plough led by a boy, while to the viewer’s left a young man plays a flute, to the sound of which two women and a boy dance. Another child holds up a fishbowl full of swallows and a cage full of fish, symbolizing that peace and happiness are not easily maintained. To the right, in an idyllic space, is a quotidian and homely scene: a mother breastfeeding her child, while a man writes and another cooks.</p>";
    NSString   *page1163 = @"<p>Las Meninas, the masterpiece of Velázquez, whom Picasso knew and admired from the age of fourteen, fascinated and inspired the artist. In his genius rendition, Picasso opens the windows of the room and elongates the background so that the exiting courtier in the distance is more easily made out, creating the situation that one has to shout to prevent his leaving. The infanta and her ladies in waiting, centre of the composition, receive all the painter’s tenderness, despite the schematic and violent lines that he uses to paint them.</p><p>None of the characters from the original painting are missing and the soft, continuous line in the lower right corner with which Picasso finishes off the figure of little Nicholas and the mastiff is admirable. As proof of the admiration that the painter felt for Velázquez is his larger than life stature, as if he were in heaven. The colour, so important for the Sevillian painter, vanishes to give way to a monochrome that accentuates the dramatic side of the painting. Two years earlier, in 1955, Picasso interprets in his own way one of the masterpieces of Delacroix, The Women of Algiers, and all because one of the women in that painting bears a surprising likeness to Jacqueline.</p>";
    
    NSString   *picassoSubtitle7 = @"Pablo Picasso";
    NSString   *page1171 = @"<p>Painted a few months before Les Demoiselles d’Avignon, his face appears to be like an experiment or sketch that he would later apply in the foundational work of Cubism. Few parts make it up though they are powerful: thick, firm lines outline his face, hair, and clothes; the colours, restricted to white, black, and ochre achieve a solid and extraordinary volume.</p><p>And those large, romantic, all-seeing eyes communicate to us his passion for life and art.</p>";
    
