    NSString   *surrealSubtitle1 = @"Introduction";
    NSString   *page121 = @"<p class=\"first\">Surrealism is a 20th century artistic movement that attempts to express through symbolic imagery aspects of the world, particularly the world of the mind, that go beyond common reality. Surrealism’s territory is the representation of the world of desire, instinct, dreams, obsessions, and in general, mankind’s irrational facets. It is a trend that is constant, appearing throughout every century, from primitive art to Mannerism or Goya.</p><p>One might consider Hieronymus Bosch (15th - 16th century) and his work The Garden of Delights as the pictorial precursor to Surrealism. The ideologue of the movement, André Breton, formulated the first definition of the movement in his Surrealist Manifesto of 1924, describing Surrealism as Psychic automatism in its pure state, by which one proposes to express -- verbally, by means of the written word, or in any other manner -- the actual functioning of thought. Dictated by the thought, in the absence of any control exercised by reason, exempt from any aesthetic or moral concern.</p><p>The Surrealist output was characterized by a limitless liberational vocation and by the exaltation of the imagination, by oneiric processes, corrosive humor, and erotic passion, all used as provocation or arms against the bourgeois cultural tradition and against all repressive forms of the established moral order.</p><p>This ample cultural movement, in its pictorial facet, yielded in Spain two of its founders: Salvador Dalí and Joan Miró.</p>";
    
    NSString   *surrealSubtitle2 = @"Salvador Dalí";
    NSString   *page1221 = @"<p>Salvador Dalí was born in Figueres, Girona, Spain. In 1922, he stayed at the Student Residency in Madrid where he got to know García Lorca and Luís Buñuel, assisting the classes of the Academy of Fine Arts of San Fernando, until he was thrown out in 1926 for declaring that none of its professors were qualified to assess him. In 1929 he meets the woman who will become his wife, Elena Ivanovna Diakonova, 11 years his senior and at the time married to the French poet Paul Éluard.</p><p>After a classical academic education, he allied himself closely with Surrealism. His painting is full of symbolism, such as insects (destruction), elephants carrying obelisks (phallic representations), eggs (the origin of life), ants (death and sexual desire) or snails and locusts (failure and terror).</p><p>His work is impressive because of the strangeness of his fantastical images, many of them inspired by the world of dreams, myths, or obsessions. Until 1937 Dalí was a fanatically dedicated Surrealist painter, true to the what he called “paranoiac-critical” method (“incited agitation of the faculties of the soul”). In 1937 he retired from the movement, whose founding group showed great political differences, and though his painting continues to be tied to intimate emotion, he starts a new period calling it “mysticism”. His techniques and styles range from classical academicism to the most groundbreaking of avant-gardes, so much so that his eclectic manner was the subject of criticism. He made incursions into theatre, fashion, cinema, photography, and jewellery, always successfully; his most famous jewel is “The Royal Heart”, made from gold and precious stones, in such a way that one ‘beats’ in its centre. All the jewellery he designed is exhibited in his Theatre-Museum in Figueres. His enthusiasm for making money earned him the nickname “Avida Dollars” (more or less translatable to “eager for dollars”) coined by Andre Bréton in 1939. His political ideology shifted in allegiance from the anarchism and communism of his youth to the totalitarianism and conversion to deep Catholicism in his maturity and old age.</p>";
    
    
    NSString   *surrealSubtitle3 = @"Dalí’s oeuvre";
    NSString   *page1231 = @"<p>This painting has become one of Salvador Dalí’s most reproduced and recognizable. It alludes to the theme that obsesses 20th century man: space-time. Following Einstein and his Theory of Relativity that profoundly shook the scientific community, the obsession over the passing of time and the existence of space were the subjects most often used by Dalí in his art. Clocks are no good, they do not work, and they are not matter, which is why he paints them soft and bent, despite their rigid machinery. It is the triumph of the dreams, controlled by nothing and by no one, the triumph of desire over reality; it is Dalí’s capacity to show, through fantastical and unprecedented imagery, the myths, mysteries, and obsessions of human beings.</p>";
    NSString   *page1232 = @"<p>In the manner of religious painting, Dalí depicts Gala as a Renaissance Virgin, holding a child. At this stage, the artist had long since abandoned his frantic Surrealist period using the paranoiac-critical method and was experimenting with intimate and mystical paintings and subjects. The child reposing on Gala is holding in turn the globe and the book of knowledge, and if one attentively examines the position of its legs, makes the shape of a cross and the number 4 as symbol of matter and the persistence of time. Above the mother and child, suspended in the air is a seashell from which hangs an egg; perhaps a tribute to Piero della Francesca and his ‘Madonna of the Egg’ (Brera Madonna). Above the altar are two of the Catalan painter’s most characteristic obsessions: to the left, a rhinoceros, whose horn is a phallic symbol and a geometric form necessary for the creation of life; to the right, a human bust so soft and lacking in consistency that it transforms into a viscous mass. The scene takes place outdoors, in a deep landscape featuring the sea and the beach, but two enormous curtains hanging on either side give the painting the appearance of theatrical or museum scenery.</p><p>Dalí was inspired by a drawing by the 16th century mystic Saint John of the Cross, preserved in the Monasterio de la Encarnación, Ávila. This origin was the defence maintained by Dalí against the many criticisms received for the very original perspective of the painting. The head of Christ, looking downwards, is the focal point of the composition. The lower part is a pleasant landscape of the bay of Port Lligat with two fishermen working. A few Velazquéan clouds and their gloomy and mysterious tones contrast with the brilliance emanating from the cross and from Christ, strengthened by the chiaroscuro, creating a dramatic effect. Dalí himself states: “My aesthetic ambition in this picture was completely the opposite of all the Christs painted by most modern painters, who have all interpreted him in the expressionistic and contortionistic sense, thus obtaining emotion through ugliness. My principal preoccupation was that my Christ would be as beautiful as the God that He is.”</p><p><br></p><p>In Crucifixion, Christ appears with an athletic and tensed body, levitating on the cross. Gala, Dalí’s wife, is depicted on her feet contemplating him expectantly; her treatment and clothing are reminiscent of Zurbarán and Murillo. In the background is the town of Cadaqués, once a holiday destination of the artist and now the home of the Salvador Dalí Museum-House. On the painting, which employs a very Baroque chiaroscuro, the painter has written: “I painted a hypercube cross on which the body of Christ is metaphysically transformed into the ninth cube, following the rules of the discourse on the shape of the cube by Juan de Herrera, the builder of El Escorial, inspired by Ramón Llull.”</p>";
    
    
    NSString   *surrealSubtitle4 = @"Joan Miró";
    NSString   *page1241 = @"<p>After his formative years at the Barcelona Academy of Arts, in 1919 Joan Miró settled in Paris where he became a part of the ‘dadaists’, exhibiting his works in various Parisian galleries. Dadaism arose in the Cabaret Voltaire in Zurich, Switzerland, characterized by its rebellion against literary and artistic conventions, mocking the bourgeois artist and his art. Dadaism created a kind of ‘anti-art’, an open provocation to the established order, and was the seed and predecessor of Surrealism.</p><p>Prior to his painting, Miró took an interest in the circle of writers and poets who would eventually become the formulators of the Surrealist universe. During a trip to Montroig, Joan Miró fell in love with the rural world of the Catalan countryside and painted a series of works straying from his Surrealist vocation, such as The Farm (1923), The Tilled Field (1923), and The Hunter (1924). Starting in 1925 he joined the Surrealist movement and travelled to The Netherlands; his series The Dutch Interiors were a product of his stay there. He experimented with collage in a series known as Construcciones (constructions), made in three dimensions.</p><p>After the invasion of France in the 2nd World War, Miró settled in Palma, Majorca, where he continued the series Constellations, in which, escaping from reality, he creates works inspired by the combinations evoked by the sky and the stars. He experimented with ceramics and, in collaboration with Llorens Artigas, he makes famous works such as the Wall of the Sun and Wall of the Moon murals for the UNESCO headquarters in Paris. Starting from the 70s he enters the world of sculpture, engraving, and ceramics.</p><p>Present at the first Surrealist exhibition, Joan Miró is the first artist that puts images and colour to the Surrealist world; the first to find a very personalized vocabulary for a gestural understanding of the subconscious and oneiric imaginary realm that the pioneers of this artistic revolution sought.</p><p>Miró has written the following: “When I stand in front of a canvas, I never know what I’m going to do - and nobody is more surprised than I at what comes out.”</p>";
    
    NSString   *surrealSubtitle5 = @"Miró’s oeuvre";
    NSString   *page1251 = @"<p>Painted at the age of 29, The Farm is the key work of Miró’s detailed and figurative period. It consists of an inventory of the masía (Catalan farmhouse) that his family owned since 1910 in Mont-roig del Camp, Tarragona, Spain. Miró himself said it was “a summary of my entire life in the countryside”. The depicted objects, animals, and landscapes enjoy a naive realist character painted in painstaking detail, known as calligrafia mironiana (Mirónian calligraphy). All the elements of this painting, animals as well as objects, are symbolical prototypes appearing in several later works by Miró, such as the ladder representing escape. Needing money (he frequently said that many of his works were the product of hunger) it was suggested to him to divide the work, in order to more easily sell it. In the end, Hemingway bought it, in its entirety, naturally, for 5000 francs, to subsequently donate it to the National Gallery of Art in Washington where it can now be seen.</p><p>On a faint blue background float signs, biological shapes, markedly defined lines, spots of color and something that is reminiscent of writing; all of it in a strange and fantastical association without any logic whatsoever, born of the world of desires and dreams. Nevertheless, these signs, lines, and spots, almost abstract, are neither automatic nor spontaneous; they are the fruit of an intense purification of an initial realist drawing in which a woman, lying down, dozes at midday. Before concluding a work, Miró worked on hundreds of sketches that he progressively schematized and shaped.</p>";
    NSString   *page1252 = @"<p>Dutch Interior I is considered his masterpiece of Surrealist painting. An automaton playing guitar and a mustachioed harlequin are the main personages of the scattered composition, made up of an entire world of details springing from their painter’s imagination. One can see: a bird with blue wings emerging from an egg, a pair of cats playing with a ball of yarn, flying fish, an insect emerging from a die, a staircase with a large ear and, in the top right, through a window, a conical shape with which Miró meant to represent the Eiffel Tower.</p><p>At this time, Joan Miró participated together with Andre Bréton’s group in a collective game known as exquisite corpse, which involves creating between the group of players a composition, either in writing or in pictures, in such a way that on each player’s turn he or she can only see the end of the contribution by the previous player and so on until the end of the game. Bréton would say that the outcome of the game was the subconscious of the group.</p><p>Fascinated by Rembrandt’s words: “I find rubies and emeralds in a dung heap,” Miró gave his title to this painting, groundbreaking in every aspect: the colour, the canvas, and the human shapes. Miró himself explains the impulse he felt in painting this work: “I had a subconscious feeling of looming disaster. Something like pain in my extremities and the breathlessness a short time before rainfall. It was more like a corporeal sensation than an intellectual perception. I foresaw a catastrophe, one that would take place soon, but I didn’t know what.” It was the Spanish Civil War and the 2nd World War.</p>";
    
